<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 12 Killed in Cambodia Grenade Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 30 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people were killed
and more than 100 injured in a grenade attack today on a
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Police said four grenades exploded in the crowd of 150-200
demonstrators outside the Cambodian National Assembly around 8.30
a.m. (0130 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Among the wounded were five reporters, including senior
correspondent Zhu Changdu of Xinhua News Agency. Zhu, 54,
sustained a serious stomach wound, but is now in stable condition
after operation in a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
Before being dispatched to Phnom Penh last October, Zhu had
worked at Xinhua's Middle East Regional Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's First Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh called
the incident "totally unacceptable and barbaric."
</P>
<P>
"The perpetrators of this heinous crime are deplorable and must
be condemned vehemently by all peace-loving Cambodians and people
in the country," a statement from Ranariddh's cabinet said.
</P>
<P>
King Norodom Sihanouk sent a message of condolence from the
Beijing to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
American Ron Abney, 55, who works for International Republican
Institute, was wounded in the thigh by shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
An interior ministry spokesman said an investigation had been
launched into the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
