<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's UF Government Refuses to Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- India's ruling United Front
(UF) government said tonight it will not resign in the wake of
Congress party's withdrawal of support for it, asserting that all
the constituents of the 14-party alliance were "solidly united as
rock."
</P>
<P>
Top UF leaders, who gathered at Prime Minister Deve Gowda's
residence after Congress withdrew its support for it, described
the Congress party's move as "unfortunate," the Press Trust of
India said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said they were confident of proving their majority
in parliament, and dismissed any possibility of the partnerships
breaking up.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from an emergency meeting chaired by Prime Minister
Deve Gowda, UF leaders told reporters that they would expect
President Shanker Dayal Sharma to allow the government to prove
its majority in the lower house of parliament at the earliest
opportunity on April 21 when parliament reassembles after a
four-week recess.
</P>
<P>
Those UF Leaders who were away from New Delhi were keeping in
constant touch with the prime minister. They expressed their
solidarity with him and pledged to unitedly foil the Congress
party's bid to topple the government.
</P>
<P>
UF sources said those leaders were now rushing to the capital
for a crucial meeting of the Front's steering committee tomorrow
to chalk out their strategy to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Congress party spokesman V.N. Gadgil said there was
no possibility of a split in the party over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Gadgil said mid-term polls were a possibility in the prevailing
situation as no party was in a position to form the government at
the center.
</P>
<P>
The remarks contradicted Congress party President Sitaram
Kesri's announcement that the party will stake a claim to form a
new government.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the UF had failed to contain the communal
forces and therefore did not deserve the Congress party's support.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
