<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers: Time to Freeze Ties With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab ministers meeting here today
at the Arab League sent a clear signal that they are ready to
freeze ties with Israel unless it gives up its settlement
activities in Jerusalem and complies with all peace accords.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League Council meeting opened this afternoon after
League chief Esmat Abdel-Meguid held a closed-door meeting with
12 Arab foreign ministers and permanent representatives of 10
other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Before the ministerial meeting, Algerian Foreign Minister
Ahmed Attaf told reporters that Arabs should reconsider their
ties with Israel which is responsible for the deadlock in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Suspending moves toward normalizing relations with Israel
would serve as a pressure on it," said Attaf, who is also the
outgoing AL Council chairman.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the resolutions adopted during the recent
Islamabad Islamic summit, Jerusalem Committee and the Gulf
Cooperation Council meetings, he called upon the Arab league to
follow suit and adopt a "firm and clear-cut stance in the face of
Israeli provocation."
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Information Minister Bassem al-Sabaa called on Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu to abandon the hard-line policy
to secure the return of the Mideast peace process on the right
track.
</P>
<P>
He said that any AL Council resolution should stress the
importance of unifying Arab stances to face the current sensitive
situation.
</P>
<P>
"The Arab solidarity and the Islamic summit resolutions
on boycotting Israel are the proper basis for dealing with the
Israeli intransigence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qatari Foreign Minister Sheikh Hamad Ben Jassem Bin Jaber Al
Thani said that he believes that all the Arabs agree on the
necessity of adopting a unified Arab stance.
</P>
<P>
"In the event of reaching such an agreement, Qatar together
with other Arab countries, will abide by it," he said, adding
that he hopes that an Arab summit will be held.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini Foreign Minister Sheikh Mohammed Bin Mubarak
al-Khalifa also voiced the necessity to adopt a clear-cut Arab
stance on suspending moves toward normalizing relations with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Egypt's views are
identical with other Arab countries, especially as far as
Jerusalem is concerned.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has no reservations against or proposal to add to the
draft resolutions prepared by the Arab League Secretariat to be
issued at the close of the ministerial meeting," he added.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara told reporters after
the ministerial meeting that Syria will propose to Arab countries
a "clearly-worded" statement that calls for cutting off relations
with Israel. And it has received "clear signals" from other Arab
countries that they are ready to approve it, he added.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua learned from sources close to the ongoing Arab meeting
that a resolution on a unified Arab stance in regard to Israel's
settlement construction in East Jerusalem will be issued at the
end of the two-day meetings, together with other seven
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Some of the ministers also mentioned the possibility of
holding an Arab summit to put a seal on the issue but they said
the date and other details are still yet to come out of the
two-day discussions.
</P>
<P>
Among other leading topics on the session's agenda are the
Arab-Israeli conflict and the implications of Israeli violations
of international law and agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League Council meeting, though a routine gathering,
is aimed at formulating a common Arab response to Israel's
settlement construction in East Jerusalem, which the Arabs said
has severely challenged the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks have broken down as Israel last
week sent bulldozers to Har Homa, the site of a planned
6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem, where
Palestinians hope to establish their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized East Jerusalem in the 1967 war and wants the
entire city to remain undivided under Israeli
sovereignty. Clashes between Palestinian stone-throwers and
Israeli soldiers plagued the West Bank and Gaza ever since,
including a suicide bombing attack that killed four people in a
Tel Aviv cafe last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
