<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Pakistan Foreign Secretary-Level Talks Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indo-Pakistan foreign
secretary-level talks continued uninterrupted on the third day
here today.
</P>
<P>
The day-long extensive talks held at an undisclosed venue were
reported to have concentrated on substantive issues of mutual
concern including the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan side was reportedly keen to achieve some progress
on the "core issue" of Kashmir while the Indian delegation has
been trying to make the dialogue broad-based involving trade and
people-to-people contact with a view to reducing the tension
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have been reiterating their respective positions on
Kashmir. Pakistan insists that Kashmir is a disputed territory and
calls for a referendum to resolve the issue, while India has ruled
out any compromise, citing the reason of secular unity and
territorial integrity of the country.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have said that the talks were being held in a
cordial atmosphere and at an expected pace -- neither too slow nor
too fast.
</P>
<P>
The four-day comprehensive dialogue on all outstanding issues
between the two countries is scheduled to conclude tomorrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
