<HEADLINE> Malaysia welcomes Singapore PM's Statement on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia welcomes Singapore
Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong's statement seeking to restore and
improve cooperation between the two countries, Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said today.
</P>
<P>
Badawi described Goh's statement as positive and said Malaysia
looked forward to such a development.
</P>
<P>
He said diplomatic ties between the two countries had never
ceased, according to Bernama news agency.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties would return to normal over time once
Malaysians got the better of their feelings over Senior Minister
Lee Kuan Yew's disparaging remarks on Johor, he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would be meeting Singapore leaders on the
matter, the minister said he had no specific plan to do so.
</P>
<P>
But he said he was willing to meet his Singapore counterpart in
New Delhi while attending the forthcoming Non-Aligned Movement
conference there if there was a need for it.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said in a statement
yesterday he was saddened that "our bilateral relations have been
upset by Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew's remarks on Johor".
</P>
<P>
He said Lee had said that it was never his intention to cause
offense and had "immediately apologized to me when the remarks
became public".
</P>
<P>
"He has also apologized to Malaysia. The Malaysian Cabinet has
accepted his apology," said Goh.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that closer cooperation between Malaysia and
Singapore will benefit both countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Goh said Singapore would do its part to restore and improve
cooperation at a pace Malaysia was comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
"We want good relations with Malaysia and my remarks on March
25 were intended to be helpful and to improve relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
