<HEADLINE> Le Pen Re-elected President of French Extreme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Jean-Marie Le Pen was re-elected
today the president of the French extreme-right National Front
(FN) party after presenting himself as the single candidate for
the post at the 10th national congress of FN in Strasbourg.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old FN president has been serving as the party's
chief since he founded it in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that Le Pen was re-elected
at a time when he has never drawn so much loathing and disgust
from the French people because of his racist ideas and demagogy.
</P>
<P>
But the latest victory of FN in the municipal election of the
southern city of Vitrolles has cast a big shadow over the
political life of France.
</P>
<P>
After being elected, Le Pen made a violent and malicious attack
against all those who oppose him, including a bitter personal
attack against the socialist mayor of Strasbourg, Catherine
Trautmann.
</P>
<P>
A former Foreign Legionnaire soldier who fought in Indonesia
and Algeria in the 1950s, Le Pen won 14.38 percent of the votes in
the 1988 presidential election, and 15 percent in the 1995
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that he does not seem to be ready to retire from the
FN presidency before the 2002 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
At least 50,000 people protested with what was described by AFP
as an "unprecedented mobilization" in Strasbourg on Saturday
against the holding of the FN congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
