<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qiao Shi Hails Sino-French Relations in Spring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qiao Shi said that the leading status and role of the Chinese
Communist Party were established in a long historical process.
</P>
<P>
He said that the leadership role of the party in China's state
affairs includes laying down political principles and orientation
of the country, major decision-making over important issues, and
recommending candidates for the seats of high level government
officials.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the major decisions and policies made by the
party have to go through the legislative process at the NPC or its
standing committee before becoming the state's will, if these
decisions fall within the field covered by the legislative power.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that ever since the founding of the People's Republic
of China, the People's Liberation Army of China has been serving
as the armed forces under the leadership of the Central Military
Commission. The Commission was set up by the state in accordance
with the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the chairman of the Central Military Commission
is elected by the NPC and is responsible to the NPC and its
standing committee.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that it is necessary to fix in an appropriate way
like this the status of the army within the state system.
</P>
<P>
He said that this does not change the leadership of the party
over the army, as the Chinese Constitution explicitly confirms the
leading role of the party in the state affairs of China, certainly
including the party's leadership over the army.
</P>
<P>
On the perspective of the prosperity and stability of Hong Kong
after it returns to China on July 1, Qiao Shi said that the rise
of stock index of Hong Kong and the increase of investments in
real estate there indicate that the Chinese compatriots and all
the investors in Hong Kong have confidence in its future.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the historic moment of resuming the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong approaches day by day, China is doing
its best to make all the preparations for guaranteeing the
successful transfer of the Hong Kong government from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that after the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) is established, China will follow the policy of "One
Country, Two Systems" formulated by Deng Xiaoping, and strictly
observe the Basic Law of the Hong Kong SAR, in order to let Hong
Kong people run their own affairs with full autonomy.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that Hong Kong will surely maintain
its lasting prosperity and stability and enter a higher stage of
construction and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Conservatives Urge Scandal-related MPs to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- British Conservative members of
parliament on Sunday urged their colleagues involved in scandals
to quit so as to save the party from a crushing defeat in the
upcoming election.
</P>
<P>
"Every Conservative candidate should examine his conscience and
say 'if I stand, will that make it more likely or less likely that
this election will be fought on policies and that the Conservative
government will get re-elected'," John Townend, a member of the
party's powerful 1922 Committee, told BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
"If it's less likely, I think there comes a time when we have
got to put the party and the country before our personal
interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another Tory legislator James Spicer said, "This is doing us an
enormous amount of damage and certainly if I were in a position
where I had to put myself or the party first, I know which I would
put first."
</P>
<P>
The Conservative party was around 20 percent behind the
opposition Labor Party in the opinion polls due to split in the
party over Europe policies and scandals of senior Tory official in
sexual indiscretions and financial irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Michael Hirst, chairman of the Scottish Conservatives, resigned
on Saturday over claims he had had a homosexual lover.
</P>
<P>
But two other Conservative MPs, Neil Hamilton and Piers
Merchant, refused to follow suit and quit as candidates.
</P>
<P>
Hamilton was allegedly involved in cash-for-question scandal in
which he received money from Harrods store owner Mohammed Al-Fayed
for asking parliamentary questions. Merchant was in a sexual
scandal and his photograph kissing a 17-year-old nightclub hostess
in a park appeared in a tabloid newspaper last week.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Major hinted in a letter to Hirst that he
would like to see Merchant and Hamilton sacrifice themselves for
the wider interests of their party.
</P>
<P>
Major announced two weeks ago the election date was set on May
1, giving an unusually long 6-1/2 weeks' notice of polling day,
which he hoped his party would use to cut into Labor's lead, But
the first two weeks have seen a series of publicity disasters for
his party, which has held power since 1979.
</P>
<P>
A poll in the Mail on Sunday Newspaper gave Labor Party 52
percent support among women against 30 percent for the
Conservatives and 14 percent for the minority Liberal Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
