<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Praises Palestinian Police for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai, in a rare move, praised the Palestinian police
for preventing escalation of violence during the Land Day protests
today.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians held large demonstrations throughout the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to mark the Land Day in protest over
Israeli policies of expanding settlements, but the protests
passed without major violence largely due to the efforts by the
Palestinian police to keep calm.
</P>
<P>
The Land Day is the anniversary of the killing of six Arabs
protesting Israel's confiscation of Arab-owned land in northern
Israel in 1976.
</P>
<P>
In Nablus, Palestinian police succeeded in blocking thousands
of protesters from attacking the Israeli soldiers guarding the
Jewish holy site of Joseph's Tomb, the scene of fierce battles in
last September's bloodshed where six Israeli soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
Five Palestinian protesters were reportedly wounded when
Palestinian policemen fired warning shots to disperse the crowd.
</P>
<P>
The head of Palestinian security forces Jibial Rajoub today
was in the West Bank town of Hebron to personally direct police
operation of preventing clashes between Palestinian protesters
and Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai praised the events in Nablus as "a good example" for
Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation in preventing
violence. Terming this weekend as a "major test for the peace
process," he said that if the week passed quietly, then it showed
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) was generally acting
against terrorism and the time was up to resume top level contacts
to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"When we identify that the Palestinian National Authority was
working seriously (against violence) with all their power, we can
respect that and can come back to continue the peace process with
the Palestinians," he said during a tour of Israeli military
outposts on the West bank.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said despite the PNA's threat of severing security
cooperation with Israel, the security contacts continued
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of the escalation of violence, Israel has
deployed tanks, armed personal carriers and snipers around major
Palestinian cities. Israel has warned the PNA that if violence
escalated into major bloodshed like in last September which
killed 75 people, Israeli troops could be sent back into
Palestinian cities to restore order.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Israel Radio reported that Miguel Angel
Moratinos, the European Union Middle East peace envoy, relayed a
message to the Israeli government from PNA President Yasser
Arafat, saying that he would fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
But Mordechai said the PNA had only partially responded to
Israel's call to crack down on terrorism. He pressed the PNA to
carry out a crackdown on the infrastructure of terrorism so as
to advance the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
