<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Plunged Into Political Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- India has been plunged into a
sudden political crisis after the Congress party today withdrew
its support for the United Front (UF) government headed by Prime
Minister Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
In a dramatic development, Congress President Sitaram Kesri
today called on Indian President S.D. Sharma and delivered a
letter to him withdrawing support for the UF government.
</P>
<P>
In the strongly worded letter, Kesri said determined efforts by
the UF government to "marginalize" Congress and allow the urgent
national issues to take a back seat compelled the party to
withdraw support for the 14-party minority coalition government.
</P>
<P>
A complete collapse of law and order in the country, failure to
arrest communal and divisive forces and the overall demoralizing
effect on the civil services were among other factors that led to
the party's decision, Kesri said.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party today announced it was staking a claim to
form a government following its withdrawal of support to the UF
government. Addressing a press conference here this afternoon,
Kesri said that Prime Minister Deve Gowda should resign and
Congress should get an opportunity to form the next government.
</P>
<P>
The top leadership of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the
biggest opposition party in the country, met today to review the
new situation.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen after the meeting, BJP leader and former
prime minister A.B. Vajpayee said no party would be in a position
to form a government on its own and a snap poll was inevitable.
BJP Vice-President Madan Lal Khurana said his party would actively
explore the possibility of forming its own government.
</P>
<P>
An emergency cabinet meeting chaired by Prime Minister Deve
Gowda was held hours after Congress announced withdrawal of
support to the UF government.
</P>
<P>
The UF government is reported to be of the view that instead of
just bowing out of office, Deve Gowda should face a trial of
strength in parliament as was done by V.P. Singh in 1990 after the
BJP withdrew support to his 11-month-old national government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Defense Minister Mulayam Singh Yadav said the United
Front government will not resign in the wake of withdrawal of
support by Congress. A steering committee of the UF will meet
tomorrow to study the new situation.
</P>
<P>
There have been mixed reactions to the withdrawal of support by
the Congress to the UF government.
</P>
<P>
Some Congress leaders supported the party's decision, while the
leadership of the Communist Party of India held Congress
responsible for sowing seeds of discord in the country. UF
spokesman Jaipal Reddy said, "It is a dirty surprise to the people
of India."
</P>
<P>
The ruling UF coalition government, with a strength of 188
members including 11 outside supporters in parliament, is short by
84 members to be in the majority after the 140-strong Congress
withdrew its support for the 14-party alliance in the lower house
of parliament which currently has 543 seats.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition BJP holds 193 seats in parliament and no
party itself is in a position to form a government.
</P>
<P>
The last general election was held in April-May last year with
no political party gaining a simple majority in parliament. As a
result, the 14-party United Front came to power on June 1 last
year with the Congress's outside support.
</P>
<P>
In the past 10-month rule, the present government has run into
a lot of troubles due to differences among the constituents as
well as with Congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
