<HEADLINE> Greek Defense Minister on Greco-Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The resolution of the Cyprus
problem according to the principles of international law and the
U.N. constitutes a decisive pre-condition for the normalization of
Greco-Turkish relations, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Greek Cypriot weekly Ta Nea (The
News), published here today, Tsohatzopoulos affirmed that his
country will maintain close defense ties with Cyprus if Turkey,
which has deployed 35,000 heavily armed troops in northern Cyprus,
does not change its stance.
</P>
<P>
"The Greek government has undertaken the political
responsibility to guarantee the security of the island, so that
the free areas of the Republic are not under the constant threat
of a new military action by Ankara," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that any "hot military incident" created by Turkey in
Cyprus will automatically translate into the mobilization of Greek
forces along the entire Cyprus-Aegean front.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is obliged to take into consideration that the
geographical distance between Greece and Cyprus no longer poses a
problem for Greece to reliably fulfil its defense obligations,"
Tsohatzopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
He added the Greek side's firm stance is that security
guarantees for both the Greek and Turkish communities on the
island can be achieved through the complete demilitarization of
the island, within an overall solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"If Turkey has the political will to accept this, we are
ready to work constructively toward this direction, but this is
impossible before a Cyprus solution can be found," the Greek
Defense Minister said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of
an Athens-backed coup.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece signed a joint defense pact in November
1993, which covers Greek military assistance to Cyprus in case of
invasion.
</P>
<P>
Athens has warned Ankara that any further advance of the
Turkish troops toward the government-controlled southern part of
the island would mean war between the two countries, both
Nato member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
