<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Urge Further Study of Coral Reef Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Scientists are becoming
increasingly concerned about the coral reef decline throughout the
world and are recommending more research into the serious problem,
a news letter from Johns Hopkins University said today.
</P>
<P>
"The corals are dying all over the world," said Hopkins
biologist and chief researcher Gary Ostrander.
</P>
<P>
Scientists do not know what is causing the coral reef
deterioration, which has accelerated dramatically since early
1980s. But their deaths may signal serious environmental ills,
Ostrander added.
</P>
<P>
However, there have been few studies to detail the phenomenon
at the molecular and cellular levels or to uncover possible
environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
Corals, like jellyfish and sea anemones, are tiny animals that
use their tentacles to catch food particles floating in the water.
Certain types of corals produce calcium carbonate skeletons -- the
coral reefs. The corals are also at the center of a complex food
web. When they die, thousands of other species are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
An example of the rapidly declining animal populations can be
seen in the shrinking number of sponges living on corals around
San Salvador island. Within three years beginning in 1994, the
number of sponges there declined by about 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We now know that San Salvador is not unique and that these
sorts of trends are going on all around the world at the same
time," Ostrander said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Appeals for Arab Solidarity on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
today urged Arab foreign ministers to freeze all steps to
normalize ties with Israel in response to Israel's Judaization
attempt on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a fiery speech to the opening session of the 107th meeting
of the Arab League foreign ministers, Arafat accused Israel of
violating peace accords by tempering the demographic features of
Jerusalem to preempt final talks on the future of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that you'll issue resolutions that will restore the
peace march and help your Palestinian brothers," he told the
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader throughout his speech made appeals to
the Muslim emotional link to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He said the Israeli settlement policy is a flagrant challenge
to the Arab and Islamic nations as well as the whole world.
</P>
<P>
"Judaization of Jerusalem is a very dangerous attempt by the
Israeli government that reneged on the peace process and wants to
liquidate the city from Arab inhabitants," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli plan is being brazenly implemented in the region
in total disregard of U.N. Security Council and U.N. General
Assembly resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League Council meeting, though a routine one, came as
a critical timing as Israel broke ground for the 6,500-unit Jewish
neighborhood in East Jerusalem, a move that has sparked
Palestinian rioting on the 10th day running and drawn serious
warnings from Arabs to shelve ties.
</P>
<P>
He described Israel's actions as a "declaration of war against
an unarmed people."
</P>
<P>
Arafat also regretted the United States' double veto on moves
in the U.N. Security Council on condemning Israel's housing plan
in East Jerusalem, saying that the U.S. has backtracked on its
1991 letter of guarantees that bar Israel from changing status quo
of Jerusalem, captured in 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians claim East Jerusalem as a future capital, but
Israel insists on keeping the city undivided under Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have reached a series of agreements
but their talks on a permanent peace accord were stuck following
the Israeli decision on a new settlement and limited withdrawal
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Arab foreign ministers' meetings are expected to
approve a Palestinian-sponsored resolution that calls for
sustained Arab and Muslim coordination in taking steps to thwart
any Israeli plans concerning Jerusalem. Most Arab ministers have
voiced readiness to sever ties with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel has diplomatic ties with Egypt and Jordan and set up
trade links with Morocco, Tunisia, Qatar and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
