<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Arab World Faces Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid warned today that the Arab world is confronted with
several challenges and problems that threaten to take toll on its
national security.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the League's ministerial council, Meguid took
account of the developments in some hot spots of the Arab world,
such as the Mideast, the Gulf region and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
On the Mideast peace march, Meguid said that the Arab world
cannot give up its rights or territories when seeking for peace.
</P>
<P>
"The maintenance of peace requires an atmosphere of confidence,"
he said, adding that Israel should contribute to building such
confidence by respecting the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Israel should see that gambling with the
region's fate and non-abidance by U.N. resolutions will negatively
reflect on itself and jeopardize the security of the entire region.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief stressed the exigency of bolstering comprehensive
security to guard Arab sovereignty which is threatened by many
problems.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to the consequences of the Gulf crisis of 1990,
which he said "still hinders achievement of genuine Arab
solidarity."
</P>
<P>
Another challenge comes from the sanctions imposed on the
Libyan people because they have caused "severe material and human
damages," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Iran of creating headaches for the
Arabs. "Iran's continued occupation of the three islands of the
United Arab Emirates is another challenge that has helped create a
fait accompli," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation on the eastern and southern borders
of Sudan continues to deteriorate, adding that the Arab league
reaffirms its keenness on establishing security and stability in
the nation and the commitment of neighboring states to the
principle of non-interference of others' international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Amid all the dark clouds, he expressed the hope that efforts
toward the solution of the Somali crisis to realize national
reconciliation will succeed.
</P>
<P>
The Arab leader concluded by warning that Israel's nuclear
program outside the international framework of non-nuclear
proliferation represents a direct threat to Arab national security
and undermines the stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
He called for international efforts to force Israel to abandon
its weapons of mass destruction to rend the Mideast a nuclear-free
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
