<HEADLINE> U.N. Environmental Body to Resume Top-Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Environmental Program
(UNEP) was set to resume on Thursday its top-level meeting
suspended last month due to bitter rows between the West and the
third world on reforms of the sole U.N. body of this kind.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Nairobi-based UNEP said this week that the
19th session of UNEP Governing Council will reopen here to
continue to discuss how to reform the UNEP's governing structure
and to raise its budgetary money.
</P>
<P>
Some new plans were expected to be put forward at the resumed
meeting, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
Fierce disputes emerged at the two-week session starting on
January 27 due to the above two issues among the participants
from more than 100 countries, causing the sudden suspension of
the meeting in the end.
</P>
<P>
From a budget of 160 million U.S. Dollars in 1991-92, the UNEP
budget provision fell to 90 million Dollars in 1996-97, with only
62.5 million Dollars actually reaching the place, causing a huge
budget gap.
</P>
<P>
On reforming a money-starved UNEP, the United States, Britain
and some other western countries suggested to set up an
"Intersessional Body" to rule UNEP during the adjourning of the
biennial session of the Governing Council.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a majority of developing countries favor the
strengthening of the Committee of Permanent Representatives
(CPR), an intersessional subsidiary body of the Governing
Council, so as to keep their enough presence in the UNEP.
</P>
<P>
The western countries finally claimed the hold-back of their
money donation, the main sources of the UNEP budget, because the
session failed to pass a plan for the UNEP reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cement Supplies Improved in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's cement importers have
stopped buying cement abroad as local supplies have proved
sufficient.
</P>
<P>
Some importers today told Zimbabwe News Agency that imports
from Zambia or any other country were only as a result of local
shortages in the past.
</P>
<P>
However, one of Zambia's largest exporters, Chilanga Cement,
said that Zimbabwean companies had stopped importing cement from
Zambia due to high prices resulting from the revised new tariffs
which came into effect on March 1.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Industry and Commerce Ministry
said,"Zambia cement is cheaper than local cement, but when we
include transport costs it comes in line with our local cement.
But the major reason we imported was as a result of shortages
last year."
</P>
<P>
He added that now that the local cement company would be
completing its expansion project in the end of year and increase
production, there is optimism that cement supplies would be
adequate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
