<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerian Cabinet Approves Customs Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian Council of Ministers
approved today a draft customs law to align the country with its
trading partners of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Algerian official sources said that the law is actually an
extension of the measures being taken to restructure industry and
to liberalize foreign trade. It is a preparatory work for joining
the World Trade Organization and for establishing partnership with
the EU.
</P>
<P>
The law also aims at improving the control of the flow of
commodities and funds for more effective protection of the
Algerian national economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the cabinet meeting, Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual said the law responds to the need to provide Algeria with
modern and effective legal tools for better movement of
commodities and funds.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the simplification of customs regulations and
measures should not ignore the accommodation of Algerian economy
in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
On the problems facing the Algerian economy, the president
called upon the government to pursue the application of reform
programs and pay particular attention to investments in small and
medium-sized establishments.
</P>
<P>
Special care should be given to combating unemployment and the
restructuring of the industrial sector, the president added.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment is the principal obstacle in the Algerian
economy. The number of unemployed people has soared to some 1.8
million while the population has reached approximately 28
million. The Algerian government is concerned that the rising
unemployment may turn into a security problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
