<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Take Tough Measures to Protect Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua
said today that China must take the strictest measures possible to
manage and protect land, in order to correct the imbalance between
the growing population and decreasing farmland.
</P>
<P>
Zou made the remark at a national land administration directors
conference which concluded today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"We must adhere to the basic state policy of 'greatly cherish
and make rational use of every inch of land, and effectively
protect farmland,'" he pointed out, adding that a one-year freeze
will be imposed on farmland-use approval, followed by a thorough
check on land use for construction.
</P>
<P>
Lack of comprehensive organization and macro-control in land
utilization has resulted in random use and abuse of farmland, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Premier stressed that subordinate land use plans must
be formed and carried out, and further use of farmland is
prohibited in principle before a modified overall program for land
utilization is put into effect.
</P>
<P>
Approval of farmland use for construction will be exclusively
validated by provincial and central governments. And the necessity
is great to revise the Land Management Law and bring under control
the entire land supply, the areas designated for urban and rural
construction, and land use purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete land management laws and statutes plus weak law
enforcement fall short of exerting effective control over random
use of farmland, thus failing to meet the needs of a socialist
market economy, he said, adding that the toughest land management
laws and regulations must be worked out and enforced.
</P>
<P>
Subsequent land system reforms will be directed at
strengthening the state's function in land management, and setting
up authoritative administration organizations to centralize land
management rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
Construction which sacrifices agriculture and cultivated land
will not only seriously affect sustained social and economic
development but also the subsistence of our future generations,
the Vice-Premier warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
