<HEADLINE> Clinton Names New NATO Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has picked Army General Wesley Clark to become the next top
commander of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), a
local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Clark, 52, will be also head of U.S. forces in Europe, The
Washington Post quoted U.S. defense officials as saying. Formal
announcement of the selection is expected today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Clark brings to the job both a knowledge of
Russia and extensive experience with the Bosnia problem. He was
the senior military member in the team brokering the 1995 Dayton
peace accords that ended the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
A West Point graduate, Clark is now head of the U.S. Southern
Command, overseeing U.S. military operations in Central and South
America. 
