<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Shrugs off Arab League Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said today that the Arab foreign ministers' decision
Sunday can only be harmful to the peace process, reported the
state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Levy made the remarks when he was speaking to reporters after
attending a Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee session.
</P>
<P>
He declared that Israel will not be deterred by the threats
made in Cairo and Rabat.
</P>
<P>
In Cairo, after hearing an emotional appeal by Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat, Arab foreign ministers approved an
Egyptian-sponsored resolution that recommends halting all steps
toward normalizing relations with the Jewish state, in response
to the Israeli construction of a new Jewish settlement at
Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Israel had declared war on the Palestinian people
by surrounding Palestine with tanks in response to protesting
Palestinians throwing stones.
</P>
<P>
On March 27, Moroccan King Hassan convened the meeting of
Jerusalem Committee of the Organization of the Islamic Conference
to discuss the crisis stemming from the settlement project. It
demanded that Israel stop the Har Homa construction.
</P>
<P>
Levy said, however, that Israel will continue on the road
to peace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, David Bar-Illan, director for policy planning and
communication at the Prime Minister's office, warned that the
Arab foreign ministers had intended to do damages to
Israel, but the damages done here will harm the Arab countries
most.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the Arab economies will suffer more
than Israel's as a result of their "boycotts and hostile
acts" against Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli President Ezer Weizman appears to be more worried
about the developments. He said that relations with the
Palestinians are not in a crisis and the government must work with
Arafat to reach an understanding toward a permanent agreement.
</P>
<P>
The president today urged both sides to make efforts to
put the peace process back on track. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
