<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Intensifies Anti-Corruption Fight: Qiao Shi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China's National People's Congress
(parliament) has intensified its efforts to fight corruption by
adopting new economic criminal laws at its latest session, Qiao
Shi, chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, said here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Paris-based Chinese language daily
"Nouvelles d'Europe", Qiao said that NPC and its standing
committee have drafted and adopted a series of laws on cracking
down on corruption and building clean government.
</P>
<P>
He said that the latest NPC plenary session, ended on March 14,
made major amendments to the Criminal Code, specifying penalties
for corruption committed by state employees.
</P>
<P>
The new criminal law has two new chapters (37 articles)
exclusively dealing with the acts of abusing office, appropriating
public funds and receiving bribes and kickbacks. The law also
stiffens penalties for neglects of duty which had serious
consequences, Qiao said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from law-making, the NPC has also participated in the
anti-corruption battle by supervising judicial system's
processing of corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
NPC delegates also supervise the investigations of such cases
and handle complaints.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said that the NPC is now working on a supervision law
which will have a major impact on the building of clean
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
