<HEADLINE> Indo-Pakistan Talks End with No Concrete Results, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The four-day foreign secretary
level talks between India and Pakistan ended here today with no
concrete results announced, but the two sides agreed to continue
their discussions in Islamabad on dates to be mutually decided,
according to Press Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
The talks, suspended in January 1994 due to differences on the
Kashmir issue, were resumed here on March 28 between Indian
Foreign Secretary Salman Haider and his Pakistan counterpart
Shamshad Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
A brief joint statement issued at the end of the talks here
today said "the two foreign secretaries discussed all outstanding
issues of concern to both sides in a frank, cordial and
constructive manner."
</P>
<P>
The statement gave no details except that the foreign
secretaries decided to continue their discussions in Islamabad on
dates to be mutually decided.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to newsmen after the talks, Indian Foreign Secretary
Haider said "a great deal of common ground has been identified" on
several substantive issues of mutual concern during the talks
which have helped in "easing" communication between the two
countries and were a first step towards the desire to resolve all
outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Haider said "these talks were useful in a number of ways. We
have a much more detailed understanding of Pakistan's approach to
the talks."
</P>
<P>
The talks were wide-ranging in character, he said, adding that
the two sides had a thorough exchange.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the impact on the talks of the current political
crisis following the Congress party's withdrawal of support to the
14-party coalition government on Sunday, Haider said the dynamics
of the discussions continued during the talks today.
</P>
<P>
He said both sides got down looking at issues in a
comprehensive way on Sunday when the events were unfolding.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Foreign Secretary Ahmad today described the bilateral
parleys as "a new beginning" in relations with India.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to follow up the new beginning with continued
interests," he told PTI at the Delhi airport shortly before
leaving for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We came here with a constructive and positive
approach. We have no illusions nor expecting any major
breakthrough or quick fixes."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, he said, was aiming at resumption of dialogue on all
outstanding issues including the "core" issue of Jammu and
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The decision of India and Pakistan to continue foreign
secretary level talks in the near future "in itself is a positive
outcome," he added.
</P>
<P>
The four-day closed-door talks were held in eight sessions.
Both sides had agreed not to disclose the details of the talks to
media.  
</P>
</TEXT>
