<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Holds Talks with Australian PM (1) Eds: more details added. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng told
visiting Australian Prime Minister John Howard today that China
and Australia, both influential countries in the Asia-Pacific
region, should join hands to push forward the development of
bilateral relations of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of their talks this afternoon at the Great
Hall of the People, Li extended his welcome to Howard, who is on
his first official visit to China after taking office more than a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the economies of both China and Australia are
highly complementary.
</P>
<P>
He noted that leaders of the two countries have held a number
of meetings to discuss many bilateral and multi-lateral issues,
and that the meeting last year in the Philippines between Chinese
President Jiang Zemin and Howard has had a particularly
significant impact on the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said he hoped that Howard's current visit can further deepen
the existing friendship between China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Saying that he is glad to visit China since he assumed office,
Howard recalled his successful meeting with Jiang during APEC's
informal summit, adding that the face-to-face meeting between the
two leaders was especially noteworthy.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that China is a very important cooperative
partner of Australia, and China's enormous economic progress
offers extremely favorable cooperative opportunities for his
country.
</P>
<P>
Li last visited Australia in 1988, Howard pointed out, adding
that the Australian government formally invites Li to come to
Australia again, an offer which Li accepted with appreciation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders agreed that there is vast potential for
bilateral economic and trade cooperation, especially in the fields
of metallurgy, livestock products, minerals and grain, which have
good prospects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Holds Talks with Australian PM (2) Eds: more details added. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li said that both China and Australia are able to provide
products needed by each other, and the two countries should make
concerted efforts to further open their markets, so as to ensure a
healthy development of bilateral trade and promote the common
prosperity of the two economies.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that Australia has taken and is taking measures
that will benefit bilateral trade, and Li welcomed this.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to explore feasibility for bilateral cooperation in
finance, insurance and social guarantee sectors. They also agreed
that the two sides will have an annual economic and trade joint
committee meeting at the vice-ministerial level in the years to
come, as well as a bi-annual meeting at the ministerial level.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Howard expressed his country's firm support
for China's entry into the World Trade Organization (WTO), saying
that this is conducive to the whole world.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that the entry into the WTO of China, as a world
trade power, can meet not only China's own needs, but also those
of the WTO, and it will result in profit for China's trade
partners like Australia.
</P>
<P>
Although China has made great economic achievements in its
reform and opening up drive, Li pointed out that China
is still a developing country, is concentrating on its domestic
modernization and constitutes no "threat" to any other country.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese side has taken note of the
Australian government's recent repeated pledge to support a "one
China" policy, hoping that Australia can adhere strictly to this
policy in regard to the Taiwan question, which affects China's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He also said he hoped that Australia can act in accordance with
the norms for international relations on the issue of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that Australia does not consider China a threat to
other countries, and hopes China can participate more in regional
and global affairs. He noted that since 1972, the Australian
government has abided by the "one China" policy, adding that on
the Tibet issue, Australia will observe relevant norms governing
international relations.
</P>
<P>
On the international situation, Li said that the current world
situation is speeding toward multi-polarization, and each country
shows an increasing orientation toward independence.
</P>
<P>
He said that China holds that it is up to the people of every
country to conduct their own affairs, and the resolution of
disputes and conflicts between nations be done through dialogue
and consultation -- not confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Howard said that his government also holds that the sovereignty
of each country and the people's rights to decide their country's
own affairs should be respected.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Li hosted a dinner in honor of the Australian
visitors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
