<HEADLINE> China's Judicial Guarantee for Human Rights Forceful: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China has made remarkable
achievements in safeguarding human rights, and its judicial
guarantees for the legitimate rights and interests of its citizens
have been "comprehensive and forceful," a justice official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiufu, vice-minister of justice, made the remark at a
press conference sponsored by the State Council Information Office
covering the publication of a document on "Progress in China's
Human Rights Cause in 1996."
</P>
<P>
Zhang briefed the press on the country's progress in building
its legal system.
</P>
<P>
Since the reform and opening up, China has concentrated on both
economic development and the legal construction, said the
vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
Since 1979, the country has enacted 31l laws and decisions on
legal issues, as well as over 700 sets of regulations and nearly
4,000 sets of administrative rules.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays, there are laws covering virtually all areas of
China's political, economic and social life, and democratic rights
of Chinese citizens have have been effectively protected with the
formulation of these laws, especially the revised Criminal Law and
Criminal Procedure Law," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that while speeding up the pace of legislation, China
attaches great importance to the implementation of laws, and the
enforcement of judicial and administrative law has been steadily
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The dissemination of knowledge of law has been done largely in
a planned and organized way, he noted, explaining that two
five-year law education publicity campaigns have been carried out
and the third five-year plan in this regard was initiated last
year.
</P>
<P>
Efforts were also stepped up to foster legal professionals as
well, Zhang said. To date, there altogether 8,265 law firms and
100,200 practicing lawyers in China; 73 overseas law firms have
been approved to set up their offices in China; and seven Chinese
law firms established their business offices abroad, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that a legal aid system has just been formed,
based on the Criminal Procedure Law and the Lawyers' Law which
went into effect this year, and designed to enable the poor and
the disabled in the community to make full use of their legitimate
rights.
</P>
<P>
To date, 47 legal aid centers have been set up in large and
medium-sized cities throughout country, Zhang said, adding that
they have handled nearly a thousand pro bono cases and had a
wide-ranging and positive influence on society.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement and inspection efforts in the country have also
been successful, he added.
</P>
<P>
As a government body in charge of prisons, the Ministry of
Justice has decided to turn the majority of the country's jails
into "modernized and civilized" facilities with adequate and
modernized equipment and sophisticated management systems.
</P>
<P>
Chinese prisons have their own characteristics, combining
punishment with education as a means of reform, and attempting to
rehabilitate criminals into law-abiding citizens, according to the
vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
The rate of recidivism in China's prisons is currently below 10
percent, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He also answered other questions concerning lawyers and the
punishment for hijackers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
