<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cadre Exchange System Improving Regional Cooperation in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To wisely combine exterior conditions and interior factors, the
state has launched the campaign of mutual exchange of grass-roots
officials and on-job training for east-west cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Huaxi Village led the country in starting on-job training for
cadres from central and western areas in 1994, and sending local
cadres to work in those areas which also sent their local cadres
to work in Huaxi in exchange.
</P>
<P>
Township officials and enterprises directors of the western
poverty-stricken areas, who have neither traveled far nor had a
ride by train, have been given the chances to study market
knowledge, corporate management in eastern areas and later to hold
deputy posts in economic departments. Officials of economic
departments from coastal areas have been sent to work as deputy
mayor or deputy magistrate in western provinces and autonomous
regions.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of cadre exchange program with the
regional Party committee of Ningxia claimed that the program is a
new step for reforming cadre administrative system, as such move
has made it possible for grass-roots officials of eastern China to
bring the concept of market economy, advanced technology and
management expertise into poor western areas, and likewise, cadres
of poverty-hit areas have the chance to learn experience and
practise them in the eastern areas.
</P>
<P>
Haijun, a 35-year-old local official of Muslim background from
Ningxia, had been engaged in administrative affairs until he was
sent to work as assistant to the mayor of Tongxiang City, east
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Haijun distinguished himself after he returned and was
appointed to be the deputy director of the management committee
for aid-the-poor economic development experimental zone of Xihaigu
Prefecture of Ningxia. Last year, entrepreneurs from eastern China
and overseas businessmen started 130 undertakings in the zone,
with the registered capital amounting to 100 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Many local officials from the western areas said that aid in
kind could be named as cooperation, the exchange of cadres will
serve as a shortcut for east and west areas in economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Officials from eastern areas who have been sent to work in
western areas also believed that they have gained a better
understanding of the western areas through working there in person.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the exchange of cadres has changed from a previous
action directed by the government to a voluntary act of many local
officials from eastern and western areas.
</P>
<P>
Through exchanges of cadres, many counties and cities of
northwest China's Shaanxi Province have been knotted in
cooperation with those from east China's Jiangsu Province, which
has also led to the growth of industrial cooperative undertakings
in Shaanxi, and have introduced 1,000 management and technological
talents and more than 500 items of advanced technologies.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the exchange of cadres is the most effective
measure to implement the economic cooperation between eastern and
western areas, which has expanded the contents of east-west
cooperation from economic sphere to include cultural aspect and
will surely usher this cooperation into a new stage.
</P>
<P>
Eastern coastal areas, mainly the Yangtze River Delta, have
built bases for cadre exchanges between the eastern and western
areas this year, while the central Chinese government departments
have listed cadre exchange as an important task for cadre
education and train in the Ninth Five-Year-Plan Period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
Information from the Ministry of Agriculture says the ministry
has launched a program to encourage cooperation of rural
industrial enterprises from the eastern and the western areas and
planned to exchange and train 10,000 directors and technological
workers through such program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 120 PKK Rebels Killed in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Some 120 members of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) have been killed in military
operations this month in southeastern Turkey bordering northern
Iraq, the Anatolia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Supported by F-4 fighters and U.S.-made Cobra helicopters, the
Turkish government troops launched attacks on the PKK militants
from northern Iraq in different areas of Sirnak Province and
killed 42 PKK rebels this month, said the semi-official news
agency.
</P>
<P>
It also reported that the Turkish security forces staged
various operations in provinces of Diyarbakir, Bingol,
Tunceli, Mardin and Siirt from March 15 to 30 and wiped out 85
members of the separatist group.
</P>
<P>
Another 14 rebels were also arrested in the operations in the
region this month, according to the Anatolia report.
</P>
<P>
The report added that a total of 19 PKK guerrillas surrendered
to the Turkish security forces in this region during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
It quoted security officials as saying that the security
forces backed by the Turkish Air Force would continue their
military maneuver in Diyabakir, Bingol, Siirt and Sirnak in a bid
to rid Turkey of the PKK, which has fought for autonomy in the east
and southeast of the country since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Over 21,000 people including PKK militants, civilians and
government troops have been killed in the 13-year-old armed
clashes between the government troops and PKK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
