<HEADLINE> S. Korea Allows Expansion of Private Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government today
announced that it will allow private groups to provide food aid
including rice for Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
from now on.
</P>
<P>
Seoul will also allow business groups to join the food aid
programs for DPRK through economic organizations, spokesman for
the National Unification Ministry said today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to today's announcement, aid for DPRK can include
food, which must be purchased from abroad. Those non-governmental
business groups contributing aid to DPRK are not permitted to do
so in the name of individuals or to collect donations or provide
cash.
</P>
<P>
It also provides that all food aid to DPRK should go through
the Red Cross of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government said it will not consider providing
large quantities of food aid in the name of government until the
DPRK agrees to participate in the Four-Party Talks with other
three partners of South Korea, the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
However, the government announcement will bring an obvious
increase of food aid to DPRK, local media predicted.
</P>
<P>
Seoul provided 150,000 tons of rice to DPRK in 1995, and since
then shipments of food to DPRK have been banned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
