<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Communications Successful in Commercialization Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Communications,
which was founded in 1908, dismantled in 1958 and re-established
in 1987, has made remarkable achievements in efforts to
commercialize its operation by focusing on management, quality and
risk-control.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the bank's 10th anniversary of re-founding,
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng wrote
inscriptions to encourage the bank to stick to the market-oriented
line.
</P>
<P>
According to its president Wang Mingquan, the Bank of
Communications has adhered to the teaching of the late leader Deng
Xiaoping "to build banks into real banks." Since its rebirth, the
bank has worked diligently to become a modern commercial banking
institution.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony held in Shanghai last Friday to mark the
10th anniversary of re-establishment which took place on April 1,
1987, Wang said the bank is the first of its kind in the country
jointly held by central and local governments as well as by a
number of state-owned institutions and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the bank's experience, Wang noted that it has set
up a managerial system in line with the requirements for a
commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank has the final say on its internal affairs, including
management, gains and losses, risk-control and financial balance,
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, the bank has opened local branches
in 89 major cities and now has over 2,400 offices in these
cities. Meanwhile, the bank has established four overseas branches
and two overseas offices in foreign countries and regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the bank's assets stood at 397.88 billion
yuan, with its deposits and outstanding loans totaling 251.96
billion yuan and 179.16 billion yuan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The bank has generated a total of nearly 40 billion yuan
pre-tax profits and given 12.8 billion yuan of interest to its
share-holders.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange makes up 30 percent of its capital and 25
percent of its profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
