<HEADLINE> Somali Warlords Make Peace Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's two major warring
factions today made appeals for political and military
reconciliation in capital Mogadishu, paving way for possible
peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's largest faction leader, Hussein Aidid who controls
most of South Mogadishu, issued a peace appeal to the other
warring factions, calling for an end to the civil war in the Horn
of Africa country.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference held in South Mogadishu, his spokesman
said Hussein Aidid is going to open peace dialogues with all the
factions including Osman Ali Atto, another warlord in South
Mogadishu, Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of North Mogadishu, and
Mohamed Ibrahim Egal, the faction leader who has declared
Somaliland in the north independent.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid is also trying to establish what he called a
National Reconciliation Council grouping Moslem scholars,
intellectuals, traditional leaders and businessmen from all the
warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Ali Mahdi today called on Hussein Mohamed and Osman
Hassan Ali Atto to join him in urgent peace talks for the
pacification of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in North Mogadishu this morning, Ali
Mahdi said the peace initiative should bring about the reopening
of Mogadishu's main seaport closed since October 1995, and the
opening of Mogadishu's international airports which remained
non-functional since the departure of the United Nations
Operation in Somalia (UNOSOM) in March 1995.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said his earlier meeting with Hussein Aidid in
Nairobi early this month was very encouraging in promoting
Mogadishu's peace process.
</P>
<P>
And his meeting with officials of the Egyptian government and
the Arab League in Cairo later on was also successful. The Arab
League has pledged their full support and facilitation to the
national reconciliation efforts in Somalia, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
