<HEADLINE> Arafat Demands Israel's Full Commitment to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Amid amounting Israeli-Arab
hostilities, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said here today all
he wants is full implementation of the peace accords, a commitment
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu fails to keep.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with an Egyptian T.V. program today, Arafat
said Netanyahu has no wish to implement signed agreements. "If
Netanyahu comes to implement what has been agreed upon I would not
mind dealing with him."
</P>
<P>
"I am not asking for the 'moon' but all that I wants is the
implementation of signed agreements," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader, a special guest to the ministerial Arab
League Council meeting, said he had requested the Arab countries
to force Israel to comply with its peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
The League approved a draft resolution Sunday night calling for
a freeze of Arab normalization steps in relations with Israel in
response to Israel's ground-breaking for a 6,500-unit Jewish
housing project in East Jerusalem, a move that has jeopardized the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have denounced the project as an attempt to
Judaize Jerusalem, a holy city to Muslims, Jews and Christians.
</P>
<P>
He said Israel, through its settlement policy, violated the
American letter of guarantees at the Madrid conference that
forbids any demographical changes in Palestinian lands, especially
in East Jerusalem during peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also regretted the U.S. double veto on
the moves in the UN Security Council resolutions to condemn
Israel's housing plan in disputed East Jerusalem, saying that
the move of the U.S. contradicts its criticism of the Israeli
settlements on Arab lands and the 1991 letter of guarantees,
signed by former U.S. Secretary of State James Baker.
</P>
<P>
"We should consider how to face up to such an attitude by
the U.S. government," he said, but did not mention any
specific measures to tackle U.S. and Israeli contempt for the
commitments they have made in the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We ask the U.S. as co-sponsors of the peace process to put all
its weight behind Oslo I and II agreements which were signed in
the White House," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increasingly tense situation in the region, Arafat
expressed belief that peace will be attained even if it is facing
all the difficulties "from those who do not keep their promises."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel have been trading accusations over
the peace crisis. Israel charged Arafat of giving green light to
terrorism while the latter denounced Israel for provoking the
violence by launching a Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also dismissed Israel's demand that the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) should control the Islamic militant group
"Hamas" as a pre-condition for resuming negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has claimed responsibility for the March 21 Tel Aviv
suicide bomb attack, killing three Israeli women and injuring
scores of others.
</P>
<P>
Arafat pinned the blame on Israel, saying that the Palestinian
suicide bomber lived inside Israel and lies out of the control of
the PNA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
