<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said here today that Australia wants to form a "truly
effective partnership" with China in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon attended by 1,000 Chinese and Australian
business people in the Great Wall Hotel in eastern Beijing, Howard
said that the Australian government and people want to have a
close relationship with China, that is built on the strength of
the people-to-people exchanges between the two countries in the
past.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize that there will be differences, but if we focus
on the common goals that we have -- we complement each other -- we
will have a truly effective partnership in the next 25 years and
beyond," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the two countries are highly
complementary in areas such as economy, trade and high
technology. He said that the Australian government encourages
exchanges and cooperation between enterprises of the two countries
and welcomes Chinese businesses to make investment in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Chinese State Councilor Song Jian echoed Howard, saying that
the two countries have a great number of similarities and great
potential for cooperation in the field of economy and trade. He
said that economic and trade cooperation between the two countries
has been growing at a rapid pace in recent years, and the future
holds bright prospects for cooperation in a range of fields from
commodity trade to hi-tech projects.
</P>
<P>
Song said that Howard's visit to China will greatly promote
Sino-Australian cooperation in all fields, including economy,
trade and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Howard also visited a chocolate factory of the Beijing Cadbury
Food Co. Ltd in the capital city this morning. He expressed
satisfaction over the business achievement of the Sino-Australian
joint venture. Chinese Minister of Metallurgy Liu Qi accompanied
Howard to the factory.  
