<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Association
for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) today expressed
sympathy and concern for the pig producers and people in Taiwan
who have suffered heavy livestock losses as a result of
foot-and-mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Taiwan-based Straits Exchanges Foundation,
ARATS also conveyed the desire of the relevant departments of the
Chinese mainland to offer aid to those financially affected.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the relevant departments of the Chinese
mainland are deeply concerned about Taiwan's outbreak of the
contagious virus that causes open sores around an animal's feet
and mouth.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, the Taiwan Affairs Office of the State Council
and the Ministry of Agriculture received inquiries from relevant
departments and people who also expressed their worries about the
disease and sympathy for the losses.
</P>
<P>
Some departments also said they are willing to send experts and
offer the newest effective vaccine to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
This fully demonstrates the strong feeling the people on the
two sides of the Taiwan Straits have for each other, the spokesman
said, adding that ARATS hopes the spread of the disease will be
under control as soon as possible, so that the economic losses of
the Taiwan people will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chen Yaochun, president of the Chinese Society of
Zootechnics and Veterinary Science, also voiced sympathy for the
situation, saying his society is willing to offer the
newly-developed Vaccine Type O, and send experts to aid their
Taiwan counterparts to quickly wipe out the disease. 
</P>
