<HEADLINE> Cadre Exchange System Improving Regional Cooperation in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- In a desolate part of northwest
China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, a new village has taken
shape on what was formerly wasteland, modelled on a village in
east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Cadres from Jiangsu's Huaxi Village, dubbed "China's richest
village", have been working in Ningxia as part of an exchange
program with Ningxia's Xihaigu, known nationwide for its extreme
poverty.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, the idea of cadres from eastern
coastal areas working with those from impoverished western areas
has become quite common. The "Huaxia Village in Ningxia" example,
one achievement of this campaign to encourage more
economically-developed areas to help poverty-stricken areas
through economic cooperation to eradicate poverty, has become a
new trend.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three years, some 10,000 officials at the
grass-roots level from eastern provinces have been sent as part of
the exchange program. Eastern provinces have signed agreements
with central and western areas for more than 10,000 economic
cooperation and mutual aid projects, and have spent two billion
yuan on these projects.
</P>
<P>
The cadre exchange has been praised by State Councillor Chen
Junsheng as an important and outstanding strategic example of
east-west cooperation, and as a "key project", "core project", and
"project hope" for inter-regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The widening economic development gap between the east and the
west, which has a number of causes, has been causing great concern
in the past several years. Industrial output value of an entire
western province or autonomous region amounts to that of only a
county in the eastern part of China, and the gap in per capita GDP
between northwestern provinces and autonomous regions and eastern
coastal areas rose from 70 yuan in 1978 to 2,000 yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
To help narrow this gap, the central government has worked out
a series of preferential policies to support development of
western areas and promote an exodus to the west of enterprises in
eastern areas.
</P>
<P>
However, some local officials in the west don't have sufficient
experience in the market economy, and some eastern businesses that
just blindly headed for the west only contributed to setbacks in
east-west cooperation and to failures of projects in the early
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
