<HEADLINE> Central China to Build Six Modern Ag Demonstration Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province,
one of China's major grain producers, is set to build six
provincial level modern agriculture demonstration zones to promote
agricultural science and technology in the province.
</P>
<P>
The province will spend three million U.S dollars building the
zones in six wealthy towns in two years to promote water
conservation, modern breeding techniques, multi-purpose
agriculture, higher yields, and wheat and maize growing.
</P>
<P>
They will focus on high-tech agricultural infrastructure
projects and integrating trade, industry and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Henan began its comprehensive agricultural development in
1988. The central government has put more than two billion yuan
(250 million U.S. dollars) into improving 1.6 million hectares of
low-yield farmland, helping add more than 1,800 kilograms of crops
per hectare.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to previous agricultural zones, the new
demonstration zones will be managed by six independent
agricultural development corporations and will introduce an
investor-owner system.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Final Sprint for Damming of the Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- With little more than seven
months left until its target date of completion, the damming of
the Yangtze River for the Three Gorges Project has entered a
critical phase.
</P>
<P>
The construction site of the world's largest hydro-electrical
endeavor is alive with the roar of bulldozers, dump trucks and
cranes. A huge eye-catching billboard reads "Damming of the river
is scheduled for Nov.15, with only 230 days left."
</P>
<P>
The water's edges in mid-river that are controlled by
cofferdams in both the upstream and downstream areas are now 460 m
and 540 m wide, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Work is proceeding smoothly for the damming and the cofferdam
construction, and the first-stage task of sinking rocks into the
water has been completed, said Lu Youmei, president of the China
Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corporation, overseer of
the project, in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
To ensure river blockage is carried out on schedule, he noted,
the builders are lowering an average 5,500 cu m of rocks into
water daily to provide a floor for the damming -- a feat that has
never been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, the riverbed on the right side of the
upstream cofferdam had been raised to an average height of 40
meters, as a result of the 380,000 cu m of rocks and concrete
blocks placed at the bottom of the river.
</P>
<P>
To keep in step with the damming work, other support projects
are being launched simultaneously, including preparation of
blocking materials on the right bank of the river, construction of
anti-leakage walls, vibration for consolidating the cofferdams,
and the clearing work within the cofferdams.
</P>
<P>
To date, some 91 percent of the total earth and rock work
volume, that is, 1.6 million cu m out of 1.7 million cu m, has
been finished for the damming and cofferdam construction.
</P>
<P>
Lu, general director of the project, noted that ISO-9000
Standards have been introduced for various damming and cofferdam
projects from the outset of the project to standardize
construction.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the project headquarters has set up various
quality control divisions for construction, in a bid to ensure
river-blockage is completed by mid-November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key RUF Members Seized by Group Loyal to Detained </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A number of key members of the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) have been abducted by elements
supporting ousted leader Foday Sankoh, diplomatic sources here
disclosed today.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the members of the new RUF and
Sierra Leone's ambassador to Guinea Mohamed Diaby were seized
when they went to a meeting in Guinea to discuss the election of
a new leader to replace Foday Sankoh who is now being detained in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The meeting ended on Saturday and the team travelled to Koindu
in eastern Sierra Leone to ''update'' RUF combatants about the
result, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
''It was there that the group ran into heavy fire and the
capture took place,'' said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a statement broadcast on national radio and TV
confirmed the abduction but blamed what it called ''misguided
elements'' in the RUF for the action.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by the Commission for the Consolidation
of Peace (CCP) named only three of those abducted. Ibrahim Deen
Jalloh, Fayia Musa and ambassador Diaby but other sources said
the expected new leader of the RUF Philip Palmer and Dr Mohamed
Barrie were arrested among them.
</P>
<P>
The statement called for the ''immediate release'' of the
abducted officials and condemned the abduction, saying the
''action will be detrimental to the overall peace process.''
</P>
<P>
Mrs Agnes Deen Jalloh, a key RUF member in Freetown, said in
an interview today that ''no demands have been made as yet.''
</P>
<P>
She said it was her understanding that the ''captured men
which include a number of Guinean security officials, would not
be kept in Nongowa and that they would be moved around.''
</P>
<P>
She disclosed that a three-man emissary group of combatants
who were sent ahead to plan the meeting were captured by renegade
RUF fighters earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
They were identified as Sahr James, Steven Kamanda and Abdulai
Mansaray. 
</P>
</TEXT>
