<HEADLINE> Indian PM Rules out His Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister H.D. Deve
Gowda today ruled out his resignation in the wake of withdrawal of
the Congress party support and declared he would prove his
majority on the floor of the Lok Sabha (lower house of
parliament), Press Trust of India said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of my resignation or suggesting
dissolution of the house," Gowda said at a meeting at his
residence here, adding that the trial of strength will be held on
the floor of the house.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he was confident of proving his majority in the Lok
Sabha, he told reporters after the meeting that "we will take care
of it."
</P>
<P>
This was Gowda's first reaction to the press since Congress
party President Sitaram Kesri withdrew the party's support to the
United Front government on Sunday.  
</P>
