<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Delay in Shaping Liberia's Electoral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The delay in the inauguration of
Liberia's electoral commission has aroused concern from the
international community over whether the presidential election
can be held in the country on May 30 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The induction of the commission, widely seen as a land-mark in
the peace process to end Liberia's seven-year-old civil war, has
been delayed twice due to controversy over who holds the
chairmanship of the organ.
</P>
<P>
The latest election of the chairman held in capital Monrovia
10 days ago resulted in a 2-2 tie between Henry Andrew and Gloria
Scott.
</P>
<P>
At that point, chairwoman of the ruling Council of State Ruth
Perry used her constitutional power to interfere and Andrew was
elected.
</P>
<P>
But then displeased Charles Taylor, the former strongest
warlord who presented Scott, claimed the process to be unfair.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha who is also
chairman of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), ordered the Liberian Council of State to "remove any
bottlenecks in inducting and reconstituting" the Independent
Elections Commission and the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Last week, General Abacha gave the Liberian provisional
authorities the deadline of April 2 to induct the two bodies to
ensure a smooth way toward the general elections.
</P>
<P>
A retired Nigerian diplomat, Issac Sagay, has been appointed
as the ECOWAS representative to the Liberian election commission
which also embraces two other representatives from the United
Nations and Organization of African Unity respectively. All the
three international delegates will not enjoy voting power.
</P>
<P>
Concerned about the success of the planned elections in
Liberia, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan has also
advised the immediate reconstitution of the two bodies.
</P>
<P>
Describing the present timetable for the conduct of the
elections as "extremely tight", Annan said any delay would
adversely affect the elections.
</P>
<P>
"For the elections to take place as scheduled on May 30, the
Liberian elections commission and its international partners must
undertake myriad complex and meticulous preparations," the U.N.
chief noted.
</P>
<P>
With only two months away from the elections, the slow pace of
preparations for the May 30 polls has also aroused concern of the
West African peace-keeping force, known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
To avoid a postponement of the elections, ECOMOG Force
Commander Major-General Victor Malu last week urged the
authorities of ECOWAS to ensure the implementation of the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
All efforts must be made to ensure that elections be held on
May 30 and the new democratic government be sworn in on June 15
as scheduled in the revised Abuja Peace Accord signed in August
1996, Malu said in the ECOMOG headquarters in Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
With the success in disarming Liberia's formal rival factions
and retrieving hidden weapons, ECOMOG has created necessary
security conditions for the holding of a free and fair election,
he told visiting acting executive secretary of ECOWAS, Mahamadou
Quhounoudou.
</P>
<P>
Malu also allayed any fear of post-election violence or
fighting while assuring the ECOWAS authorities and the
international community that ECOMOG is in position to contain and
effectively tackle anyone who might lose election and try to
cause problem.
</P>
<P>
As Annan put it: "The prospects for peace in Liberia now seem
to be more promising than at any time since the start of the
civil war. Whereas, much remains to be done." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
