<HEADLINE> Weah Threatens to Abandon Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's George Oppong Weah has
threatened to boycott the World Cup tie between his country and
Egypt on April 6 over the country's inability to settle an
outstanding 39,000 U.S. dollars allowances owed him.
</P>
<P>
Unless the arrears was reimbursed by the government, he would
not show up for the World Cup preliminaries against Egypt because
"I want to teach the people some lessons," said the world's top
soccer player and AC Milan marksman, according to a report
reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Weah said the amount was incurred during the African Nations
Cup qualifier against Zaire last October and other unnamed matches.
</P>
<P>
He also advised the government to settle all outstanding
allowances to other professional players incurred over the years.
</P>
<P>
"Once I am not coming, you can be sure what it means. Other
professionals will also boycott the game," he said.
</P>
<P>
Weah said he had made a lot of sacrifices for the growth of
football in Liberia and "it is time government shows the same
appreciation."
</P>
<P>
"We are tired of empty promises. Let the word go forth that we
will not come for the Egypt match, if the government can't meet
its obligations to us," he warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
