<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Team to Climb Mt. Qomolangma for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani mountaineers are
going to make their maiden attempt to conquer the world's highest
Mt. Qomolangma on the border of Nepal and China in May, a renowned
Pakistani climber said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's first Qomolangma expedition, arriving here last
week, will scale the 8,848-meter mountain on the north face in the
Tibet Autonomous Region of China probably by the end of May, team
leader Nariz Ahmad Sabir told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
According to Sabir, an accomplished climber who made the first
ascent of the west ridge of the 8,611-meter peak K-2 in Pakistan
in 1981, his 10-member team will leave here in early April for
Lhasa and establish the base camp in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
Three Chinese climbers will join the Pakistani team in the base
camp which is expected to be set up at 5,500 meters above sea
level, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sabir said the expedition is a unique commemoration of the
golden jubilee of Pakistan's independence.
</P>
<P>
The whole operation, expected to cost 400,000 US dollars, is
mainly sponsored by Hub Power Company Ltd. (HUBCO), Pakistan's
first private sector power plant which provides about one-sixth
supply of electricity in the country, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
