<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Congress Party Dislodges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- In a dramatic development on
Sunday, the Congress party withdrew its support to the
ten-month-old United Front (UF) government headed by Prime
Minister H.D. Deve Gowda in a bid to check the sustaining erosion
of the party's fortune since its debacle in the general elections
held last year.
</P>
<P>
Congress party President Sitaram Kesri, who presented a letter
to President Shanker Dayal Sharma conveying his party's decision
to withdraw support to the government, also announced that the
party staked claim to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
Kesri's move, which took even many in his party by surprise,
put a question mark over the fate of the government with no clear
indication as to what political scenario will emerge at the next
stage.
</P>
<P>
The move came earlier than expected though the relations
between the Congress party and the ruling UF have been
deteriorating over the past few months, especially after the
opposition Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), allied with another local
party, recently formed a popular government in the most populated
Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
The 14-party UF and the Congress party entered into a temporary
alliance in the context of a hung parliament arising out of the
general elections held in April and May last year.
</P>
<P>
During the elections, the 112-year-old Congress party suffered
an unprecedented defeat by only garnering about 140 seats in the
543 seats Lok Sabha (the lower house of the Indian parliament).
</P>
<P>
The BJP, which is dubbed as radical "communal forces," won 160
seats, emerging as the largest party in the country. The BJP and
its allies formed a minority coalition government which collapsed
within only two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The UF, with a strength of only 177 seats in the parliament,
formed a new coalition with outside support from the Congress
party on June 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party hoped that its alliance with the UF could
help contain its main rival, the BJP, and in the meantime buy some
time for the party to revitalize itself to face a fresh poll at an
appropriate stage.
</P>
<P>
However, the honey moon between the Congress party and the UF
did not last long and the relations between them began to worsen
after Kesri replaced former prime minister P.V. Narasimha Rao as
the leader of the Congress party in September last.
</P>
<P>
As the relations between the two groups deteriorated, the
emerging view among the Congress party leaders was that the UF
experiment had failed to checkmate the rise of the BJP, which
emerged victorious in both Uttar Pradesh and Punjab through
manipulative coalition efforts.
</P>
<P>
Thinking that a weak Congress party will help it to stay longer
in power, the UF had not only refused to lend support to the
Congress party in the recent local elections in Uttar Pradesh and
Punjab but also filed its own candidates against those of the
Congress party in a number of by-elections to vacancies in the Lok
Sabha.
</P>
<P>
The BJP benefited from all these discords between the Congress
party and the UF, which stirred lots of grievances within the
Congress party.
</P>
<P>
Apart from failing to contain the BJP, the UF government had
also contributed to the Congress party's loss of image by
launching probes against its leaders in a selective manner and
jeopardizing the party's electoral prospects at different levels
of elections.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party leaders were upset that as many as 100
investigations by law enforcement agencies, including the Central
Bureau of Investigation, had been launched against incumbent and
former senior Congress party leaders and even against Kesri, the
party chief.
</P>
<P>
Four scandals, for example, are under investigation against
former prime minister P.V. Narasimha Rao and two against Kesri.
</P>
<P>
As the Congress leaders saw it, a government surviving on their
support in parliament was out to tarnish them by using the law and
relevant enforcement agencies in a selective manner.
</P>
<P>
What irked Kesri and his supporters most, according to an
editorial published by Indian newspaper The Hindustan Time today,
was that the major UF leaders did not hesitate to fish in the
troubled waters of the Congress party by preferring to talk to
Narasimha Rao even after Kesri had taken over as the Congress
party president.
</P>
<P>
And in recent weeks, the UF leaders preferred to have informal
meetings with Sharad Pawar, the actual leader of the Congress
party's parliamentary group and a known opponent to Kesri, than to
hold consultations with the Congress party president.
</P>
<P>
Disappointed by the UF's handling of its relations with the
Congress party and annoyed by the constant erosion of the party's
fortune, Kesri and other Congress party leaders have repeatedly
warned the Front against taking the party's support for granted
and urged it to take correct measures.
</P>
<P>
In one of such warnings, Kesri told the UF government on
October 6 last year that "if the Congress party becomes weak, this
government will go."
</P>
<P>
The UF, however, has failed to take such warnings seriously. It
has not only ignored them but sometimes even ridiculed them as
nonsense, embarrassing the Congress party with a further damage to
its image.
</P>
<P>
Like the boy in the fable who cried wolf once too often, the
Congress party finds itself alone when it abruptly announced on
Sunday its decision to withdraw support to the Deve Gowda
government after threatening to do so for so many times in the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
As in the fable where the wolf ultimately forced the boy to
tell the truth, it is the UF and its leaders who seem to have made
up the mind of the Congress party.
</P>
<P>
In his strongly-worded letter to the president on the party's
withdrawal of support to the government, Kesri accused the UF
government of making "determined efforts" to marginalize his party
and of serious failure to joint hands with the party to contain
the BJP and other "communal forces" in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0097 </DOCNO>
