<HEADLINE> Australia To Focus trade On South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Australian Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister for Trade Tim Fischer will this week lead the first
trade mission to South Asia in more than a decade as part of the
Howard Government's new Asia-focused bilateral trade strategy.
</P>
<P>
Business people from 20 Australian companies involved in
mining, infrastructure, engineering, finance, shipping and the
medical industry are accompanying Fischer on the nine-day trip,
which will include visits to Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal and
Bhutan.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said today that the aim of the mission is to
expand trade and investment with the region, where economic
reforms are starting to generate substantial opportunities.
</P>
<P>
According to Official figures, Australia's exports to Pakistan
is growing at annual rates of 30 percent to 35 percent, totaling
260 million Australian dollars (202 million US dollars) in 1996,
while exports to Bangladesh almost doubled to 226 million
Australian dollars (176 million US dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan are much smaller markets, but, the sources
said, they also offer some investment possibilities, such as
hydroelectric power generation in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
India is the main South Asian market, taking more than one
billion Australian dollars in the country's exports a year, but
the current mission will not go to India, which was the subject of
last year's New Horizons promotional effort.  
</P>
</TEXT>
