<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crimes That Jeopardize State Security Becoming Less Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- There is only a very limited
number of criminals in Chinese prisons who have committed crimes
of endangering state security but were sentenced for
counter-revolutionary crimes.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by vice-minister of justice Zhang Xiufu today
when meeting the press here. He disclosed that there are currently
2,026 people serving sentences for jeopardizing state security,
meaning 1.6 per million people, and only 46 of every 10,000
prisoners in the country, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Those serving sentences for counter-revolutionary activities
include people involved in prison riots and terrorist activities
who were convicted of counter-revolutionary crimes under the
previous criminal law, he said.
</P>
<P>
When those people are factored out, the number of people
accused of jeopardizing state security becomes much smaller, the
vice-minister noted, adding that such offences are now defined as
common criminal offences under the revised criminal law.
</P>
<P>
As the standard of living improves and public awareness of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics increases, the
crime of sabotaging state security will become less common, Zhang
explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Hail Resolution on Freezing Ties With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries have hailed the
draft resolution approved Sunday night at the meeting of Arab
League Council that called for suspending Arab normalization of
relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposed by Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and
Syria recommended Arab states reactivate the economic boycott of
Israel, stop normalization steps, close Israeli offices and
missions and pull out of multilateral talks on aspects of Mideast
peace.
</P>
<P>
Egypt said it holds no reservations against the resolution
which is a prime recipe for the ailing peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters after
Sunday's session the resolution is directed to the Arab
countries that have opened offices in Israel.
</P>
<P>
"But when the peace process faces such potential obstacles
owing to the Israeli policy, it is natural enough they reconsider
their stances," he added.
</P>
<P>
"It mirrors the feeling Arabs have now," he said, adding that
the Arabs can never accept the building of settlements or any
manipulation in the Israeli redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Israel must act in a way allowing other countries to continue
to push forward relations with it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Farouk Qaddoumi, the head of the PLO political
department, said the resolution is good at the current stage.
</P>
<P>
"The move is premised to have a political impact on the
recalcitrant party that is offering no service to the peace
process," he added, in an allusion to Israel.
</P>
<P>
He noted that what matters is the response to such resolutions,
but he denied that some Arab countries showed reservations about
the resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Qaddoumi, asked on how Jordan and Egypt will implement the
resolution, said "we are talking about the steps recently taken by
some Arab countries, not about those who have signed peace
treaties with Israel."
</P>
<P>
Israel has diplomatic ties with Egypt and Jordan and set up
trade links with Morocco, Tunisia, Qatar and Oman.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara referred to the tribute
paid by other Arab delegates to the resolution and expressed "full
satisfaction" with the outcome reached by the Arab League Council
meeting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Other Arab countries, such as Qatar, Bahrain, Lebanon and
Algeria have also voiced support to the move and readiness to
implement it as soon as recommendations are fully studied.
</P>
<P>
In the first Israeli reaction Sunday night to the Arab League's
resolution, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu urged Arab countries
to "think of their interests on the long run."
</P>
<P>
"I believe peace is in the interests of Egypt and Jordan, two
countries bound by peace treaties with Israel, as well as other
Arab countries," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Palestinians to think over the "necessity of
achieving peace for the sake of the two sides."
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the 22-member league, during their
evening session, approved the resolution as a joint Arab response
to Israel's Judaization attempt on Jerusalem through building
Jewish settlement on the Arab sector of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League Council meeting, though a routine one, came as
the Mideast peace was jeopardized by Israel's ground-breaking for a
6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem. And Palestinian
riots against the settlement has entered the 11th day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Meat Exports Rocked By Disease Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian ban on imports of
meat and live cattle from Victoria and New South Wales (NSW)
following anthrax outbreaks in several parts of the two main meat
export states has rocked the country's 2.75 billion US dollars
meat export industries.
</P>
<P>
A top Indonesian Government official in Jakarta was reported as
saying today that the ban imposed on March 10, would be lifted
three weeks after the last reported case of anthrax.
</P>
<P>
Local officials are concerned that the ban imposed by the
Indonesian Government on meat imports from Victoria may be
extended because of new outbreaks in some parts of NSW.
</P>
<P>
The chief veterinary officer with the NSW Department of
Agriculture, Dick Jane said, the State's animal health officers
had been dealing with wide-spread anthrax outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
They had occurred during the same 42-day quarantine period as a
Victorian outbreak that threatened markets in Korea and Japan and
closed the Indonesian and Thailand markets.
</P>
<P>
Jane said, there had been anthrax outbreaks at Nyngan,
Narrandera and Bourke in NSW State, one of which killed 16 cattle,
and "a couple of cases" at Condobol in last September.
</P>
<P>
However, NSW Agriculture Minister Richard Amery told ABC
Television today that "the Indonesian action was probably a
precautionary one, we believe the ban will be short-lived and the
matter will be resolved."
</P>
<P>
He said, "NSW had eight to 15 outbreaks of anthrax a year, with
only six last year and they were easily handled, it is not that
bad at all, we've learned to live with anthrax and how to handle
the outbreaks for many decades."
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, since the outbreak was reported
on 26 January, the disease killed almost 200 cattle in Victoria,
83 properties were confirmed as being affected by anthrax.
</P>
<P>
Anthrax is a highly infectious cattle disease that leads to
ulcerating nodules, lesions in the lungs and blood poisoning, it
can be transmitted to humans handling infected meat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
