<HEADLINE> S. Korean Foreign Exchange Reserves Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The foreign exchange reserves of
the Bank of Korea (BOK) have fallen below the 60 billion
U.S. dollars mark for the first time in the 22 months.
</P>
<P>
After hitting a record high of 68 billion dollars at the end of
last June, the central bank's foreign exchange reserves have been
steadly declining mainly due to the widening current account
deficit and slow inflow of foreign capital for direct investment,
senior BOK officials said today.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's current account deficit increased by 51 percent
to 5,581 million dollars during the first two month of 1997 from
the 3,705 million dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Largely affected by the recent depreciation of the Won against
the Dollar, foreign investment in local stocks has been sluggish,
shifting from a net inflow stance in January to a net outflow
situation in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
