<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Justice Ministry Briefs Press on Bao Tong, Wang Dan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Zhang Xiufu, China's
Vice-Minister of Justice, spoke with the press in Beijing today on
the conditions of Bao Tong and Wang Dan.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that Bao Tong was released in May of last year after
serving his sentence, but according to the court's verdict, was to
be deprived of political rights for two years during which he is
placed under the watch by relevant departments in accordance with
the law.
</P>
<P>
When asked why Bao Tong has not returned home, the
vice-minister explained that the apartment where Bao had lived is
state property that had been allocated to him as his original
position entitled him to and that departments concerned considered
it inappropriate for him to continue to live in that apartment.
</P>
<P>
He said that the relevant departments have provided Bao with
alternative housing, but Bao's family did not agree with this
arrangement. The matter is still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
These departments have been taking good care of his livelihood,
and have invited top-notched medical experts to treat his
diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bao once held a position in the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Bao was arrested in 1989 for breaking the law by leaking
important state secrets and inciting others to resist and hinder
the implementation of state laws.
</P>
<P>
He was later sentenced to seven years in prison and deprived of
political rights for two years by the Beijing Intermediate
People's Court.
</P>
<P>
In answer to a question about why Wang Dan has not been let out
on bail for medical treatment, Zhang said that it is because Wang
is in a good health and does not meet the requirement for being
released on bail.
</P>
<P>
He said that Wang's parents visited him in jail during Spring
Festival and spent the holiday with him. Wang even joined a
singing contest in prison, Zhang added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that Chinese prisons follow humanitarian
rules. According to the law, prisoners suffering from serious
ailments who meet the requirements are eligible for being freed on
bail for medical treatment. An average of 25,000 prisoners have
been released on probation for medical treatment every year in
China, according to the vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
Wang was sentenced to 11 years and deprived of political rights
for two years by the Beijing No.1 Intermediate People's Court for
plotting to subvert the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
