<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nationwide Inspection of Chinese Accountants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- China will start holding annual
inspections this year to standardize the work of certified public
accountants.
</P>
<P>
A circular by the Chinese Institute of Certified Public
Accountants (CICPA) says that the institute will inspect at least
ten percent of the accounting and auditing agencies in China, and
that those about which there have been complaints by the public
will be the primary target of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
"The inspection will look into whether those agencies are
operating in accordance with laws and regulations, and will see
how the nation's first CPAs are doing in their business,"
explained an official with CICPA.
</P>
<P>
Accounting agencies are required by law to have a minimum of
300,000 yuan in registered capital, more than ten accountants,
including at least five CPAs, and have an established office.
</P>
<P>
"Any agency that is found to be providing companies with false
statements will be seriously penalized," the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
