<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Sudanese Flee to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Over 400 Sudaneses fled their
homes in southern Sudan and entered northeastern Uganda, a report
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Most of the refugees are between 12 and 25, The New Vision
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The refugees settled in Kotido district claimed they fled
their homes to avoid forced recruitment both by government troops
of Sudan and rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) which
has taken up arms against Khartoum since 1983.
</P>
<P>
Limmy Lomakol, the deputy co-ordinator of World Food Program
project for Karamoja, said the refugees are in acute need of
food, clothing and shelter.
</P>
<P>
He said his project has put in place provisional arrangements
including supply of food and construction of sanitation
facilities and shelters under the food for work scheme. Kotido is
part of Karamoja region in Uganda's Northeast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
