<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Students Learning About Traffic Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Some 500,000 primary and middle
schools across the country will soon be issued two million sets of
illustrations on traffic rules to help teach students more about
road safety.
</P>
<P>
Today is the second "Safety Day" for China's more than 200
million primary and middle school students. The illustrations are
being provided by the State Education Commission (SEC) and the
Ministry of Public Security (MPS).
</P>
<P>
The illustrations contain colorful cartoon figures and captions
to teach students how to ride a bicycle and cross the road in a
safe manner and not to read while walking.
</P>
<P>
Liu Bin, vice-minister in charge of the SEC, said that rural
schools are weak in safety education and asked local education
agencies to pay more attention to safety in rural schools,
especially primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Liu is encouraging students to wear yellow hats and to exit
their schools in single file so that the large bright group will
be more obvious to drivers.
</P>
<P>
He has also called on primary and middle schools to organize
fire, earthquake, and flood drills to teach students how to save
each other in emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Seven ministries and commissions including the SEC, the MPS,
the Ministry of Communications, and the Ministry of Railways
jointly decided last year that the last Monday of March each year
would be "Safety Day" for primary and middle school students.
</P>
<P>
Vice-premier Li Lanqing spoke on national TV urging all of
society to pay attention to child safety.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, among primary and middle school
students, nearly one in ten thousand is killed annually by
accidents in China, and 4,000 to 5,000 students die in traffic
accidents each year.
</P>
<P>
Public Security Vice-minister Mu Xinsheng said today that the
MPS has asked traffic policemen to watch traffic near school gates
while students are going to or from school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
