<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unleaded Gasoline Used to Reduce Air Pollution in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Tehran, one of the worst air
polluted capital cities in the world, has started distribution of
unleaded gasoline at 44 petrol stations in a bid to reduce
pollution, a press report said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Jumhuri Islami reported that the move of the
petrol stations is organized by the Oil Ministry-affiliated
National Refining and Distribution Company.
</P>
<P>
The company said that drivers have easy access to unleaded
petrol over the city and the measure would help to reduce air
pollution as well as contribute to automobile's engine efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Iran is presently producing 4 million liters of unleaded
gasoline a day at Arak refinery in central Iran.
</P>
<P>
The production is anticipated to increase by threefolds or
12 million liters a day upon completion of the Bandar Abbas
refinery in the south this year, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The switch from leaded gasoline to unleaded gasoline is
part of the nationwide drive to fight against air pollution in
the country, Tehran in particular.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that Tehran is facing serious air pollution
with two tonnes of lead entering the air every day. About 80 percent
of the air pollution was caused by cars.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the poisonous gas released by automobiles in
the city will cause various disease related with liver, kidney,
spleen, brain, bones and muscles.
</P>
<P>
With a population of about 10 million, there are some three
million cars in the city. The percentage of poisonous gas in the
air of Tehran city is as some six times as the permitted figure.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, the Iranian government has also taken
some specific measures to reduce air pollution in the city, such
as changing the city's gasoline-engine taxis and buses into
gas-engine cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province to Add Local Telephone Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province,
which has been relatively backward in its telecommunications until
quite recently, has increased its telephone numbers to seven
digits, while bringing the total number of local telephone
networks to 12.
</P>
<P>
The province consolidated various areas, allowing it to reduce
the number of telephone area codes from more than 80 to the
present 12.
</P>
<P>
Total handling capacity of the provincial public
program-controlled switchboards is more than one million lines,
96.8 percent of which are digitally-controlled.
</P>
<P>
Telephones in areas at or above the county level are now all
covered by program-controlled switching, with those at or above
the prefecture level covered by digitally-controlled
telecommunications.  
</P>
</TEXT>
