<HEADLINE> Consuming Idea Changing in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Citizens in Guangzhou, capital
of south China's Guangdong Province, are spending more on
household appliances and clothing, and those with higher incomes
have shifted their shopping sights from food to
telecommunications, education and travel.
</P>
<P>
The average living expenses for urban dwellers reached 9,379
yuan (about 1,117 US dollars) last year, an increase of 9.7
percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the local statistics bureau, in 1996, the rise in
the urban dwellers' spending on durable consumer goods and
clothing well-exceeded that on their spending on food.
</P>
<P>
Air conditioners, motorcycles and home video-audio
entertainment systems are becoming the new favorites for families,
replacing color TVs, refrigerators and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, on average every 100 families in the city
have 79 air conditioners, 14 motorcycles and 49 stereo systems, up
37.2, 13.2 and 19.7 percent from the previous year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In this most developed southern city, both men and women now
want to dress well, as evidenced by the 15.5. percent increase in
spending on clothing last year.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications, education and tourism are also luring
more and more money from residents' pockets. By the end of
1996, there were 84 telephones for every 100 families -- who are
now setting their sights on mobile telephones -- while multi-media
computers are making a speedy entrance into ordinary households.
</P>
<P>
Last year, residents' spending on food rose by only 6.9
percent, while that on main food items and cooking oil
fell. Spending on rice and peanut oil dropped by 5.9 and 7.1
percent, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
