<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sets up Monitoring Station in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States has set up a
high-tech monitoring station at Fort Portal town in western
Uganda to keep track of the war in Zaire, The East African
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper quoted sources close to the Ugandan Army
commander in Kampala as saying that the station would enable the
U.S. Military to respond quickly to protect American interests in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The sources stated that the U.S. army was setting up two other
monitoring bases in Brazzaville, Congo, and Kigali, Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses in Fort Portal told the paper that at least four
U.S. Marines are manning the station, which is about two
kilometers from the city center.
</P>
<P>
The Marines which rented two houses and paid 1,500 U.S.
Dollars per month have been in Fort Portal for three months but
have kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
Two satellite dishes can be seen in the compound and a man
with an AK-47 who is wearing a grey uniform guards the house, the
paper noted.
</P>
<P>
A source in the Army Commander's office of Uganda told the
regional paper that "the Americans regularly brief us on their
monitoring."
</P>
<P>
The Kinshasa government has repeatedly accused both the United
States and Uganda of supporting Banyamulenge rebels now fighting
the government of President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government denied the accusations, saying that the
only support it gives the rebels is moral.
</P>
<P>
The weekly quoted the Ugandan Military Intelligence sources as
saying that Uganda is suspected by France of being used by
America to promote "Anglophonism" and reduce French influence in
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, schools in Rwanda now teach English as
another national language and the country's leaders have shown
interest in joining the Commonwealth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
