<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 90 Percent of Zambian Sewerage Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Ninety percent of Zambia's
sewerage treatment facilities are defective leading to pollution
of most rivers and streams in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to an annual economic report from the Finance
Ministry, the defective city sewerage treatment facilities and
lack of in-house effluent treatment facilities in most industries
lead to discharge of untreated effluents into the rivers and
streams.
</P>
<P>
It cited the Kafue and Kafubu as the two most polluted rivers
in the country resulting in severe weed encroachment, which has
exerted mechanical pressure on infrastructures such as bridges
and has adversely affected water quality.
</P>
<P>
The report also indicated that despite the progress made to
protect and conserve the environment, there is still an increase
in land degradation, deforestation, poaching and deterioration in
waste management standards.
</P>
<P>
Depletion of the forest has reached alarming proportions with
the annual deforestation rate being estimated at 0.5 percent,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
