<HEADLINE> Zairean Soldiers Wander into Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- An unknown number of heavily
armed Zairean government soldiers have been spotted at a fishing
camp along the border near Mwense in Zambia's Luapula Province,
local press reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean soldiers, armed with rifles and grenades, have
grouped at the Manandwe fishing camp and it is not clear where
they are heading, Luapula Permanent Secretary Maybin Mubanga said
on Sunday in Mansa, provincial capital of Luapula.
</P>
<P>
Zambian government officials have rushed to the spot to assess
the situation.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted other sources as saying that the Zairean
soldiers hope to surrender to the advancing rebel forces but it
is unclear whether they intend to do that on Zambian soil.
</P>
<P>
Mubanga said over 1,000 refugees from Kasenga town in Zaire
have entered Zambia following the capture of Kasenga by rebel
forces last Friday. The mass exodus was triggered by reports that
the Zairean army want to launch a major counter offensive to try
to recapture Kasenga.
</P>
<P>
He said there is a crisis at Kashiba primary school where the
refugees are kept because the Zambian authorities do not have
food for them.
</P>
<P>
Fighting continued in Zaire between government troops and
rebel forces though the two sides agreed to negotiate a peaceful
solution at a special summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) recently held in Lome, capital of Togo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
