<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese Province to Tighten Price Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province has launched a program to control price rises of consumer
goods, according to the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
Thirty kinds of commodities and service fees, which account for
80 percent of urban citizens' living expenses, were put under
close supervision and control, according to Li Yunlong, director
of the Provincial Bureau of Commodity Prices.
</P>
<P>
The commodities and services include grain, vegetables,
pork, medicines, fuels, electricity, water, chemical fertilizer,
and education charges, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The province has promised to keep the rise in the retail price
index below six percent, and that in the consumer goods price
index below eight percent in 1997, he said..
</P>
<P>
Illicit collections of fees and illicit price hikes will be
banned, he said, adding that the government will curb price
increases and bring down the price level by applying regulating
funds, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is dropping to normal through coordinated efforts,
but pressure from price increases is still strong and has a great
effect on people's lives, especially those who have low incomes
and displaced workers in state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A major heavy industrial production center in China,
Heilongjiang has a large number of state-owned enterprises, many
of which are operating at a loss.
</P>
<P>
The province is now taking legal and economic measures to
maintain basic price stability for its 36 million
residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
