<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Rescues Returnees From Zaire, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army has rescued in
its northwest region about 250 Ugandan returnees from Sudan and
Zaire, local newspaper the New Vision reported.
</P>
<P>
The returnees, including 101 children and 52 women, were
pelted, abused and accused by local residents of being
pro-rebellion with their houses burnt, their relatives killed and
their properties looted when the returnees arrived at Kamadi
border post in Arua district along the Uganda-Zaire border on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Arua was the most harassed district by the rebels of the West
Nile Bank Front.
</P>
<P>
The returnees, who had been soldiers of the defunct army of
the former dictator Idi Amin and their family members, were
transferred to a resettlement camp.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had recruited them in eastern Zaire and southern
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese and Zairean rebels who controlled southern Sudan and
eastern Zaire respectively asked Ugandans lived in the regions to
return home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
