<HEADLINE> Central China Province Sets Seed Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan province
has set standards on seeds to help protect farmers' interests.
</P>
<P>
The name, site and date of production, quality, planting
instructions and suitable uses of each variety of seed should be
clearly written on all seed packages, according to a local
regulation to go into effect on May 1.
</P>
<P>
Seed packets that do not bear the information will be
considered sub-standard, the regulation pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Hunan, as a major grain producer in the country, has reported
several cases of fake or poor-quality seeds.
</P>
<P>
The local government attributed this partly to the lack of a
well-defined standard.
</P>
<P>
The regulation will help improve management of seed production
and guide farmers choose quality seeds, said the local government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province worked out standards for asparagus,
which is used as a raw material in paper production.
</P>
<P>
Hunan now has 660,000 ha of land planted with asparagus, with
annual output of 700,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
