<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imperial Mausoleum Attracts Overseas Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hualong Imperial
Mausoleum in north China's Hebei Province has attracted more and
more overseas Chinese since 1995, when the ashes of Pu Yi, the
last emperor in Chinese history, were brought there.
</P>
<P>
Situated west of the Chong Tomb of the Emperor Guangxu of the
Qing Dynasty (1644-1911), the Hualong Mausoleum was co-constructed
by a Hong Kong company and the Gongyi Cooperation of Yixian County
in Hebei.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the mausoleum began in September 1992 and was
completed in May 1994. The mausoleum has over 50,000 small burial
chambers, serving mainly for Chinese people, especially those
overseas Chinese who want their ashes returned to their motherland.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Shiyi, director of the Hualong Imperial Mausoleum, said
that the facility will offer various services, such as
computerized documentation of the death records, and providing
flowers for the burial chambers.
</P>
<P>
The mausoleum was approved by the Ministry of Civil Affairs and
the Hebei Provincial Department of Civil Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
