<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Vietnam Agree to Boost Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Vietnam have agreed to
raise economic cooperation, particularly in trade and investment,
to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh made these remarks
here today after holding talks with Vietnamese leaders.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two countries stood at 610 million
U.S. dollars in 1996 and was expected to shoot up to one billion
this year.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have agreed to encourage Thai businessmen
to increase investment in Vietnam. Now of the 74 projects licensed
in Vietnam, Thailand ranked ninth among all foreign countries and
fourth among ASEAN countries following Singapore, Indonesia and
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, they also addressed other issues of common
concern, including Thailand's further assistance to engage Vietnam
in more ASEAN activities, to implement ASEAN's free trade area
regulations and to organize successfully the sixth ASEAN summit in
Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit arrived here Sunday afternoon for his first visit to
Hanoi after becoming prime minister in November 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
