<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Surplus Labor Forces Getting Prosperous in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Rural surplus labor forces in
northwest China's Gansu Province have stepped out of poverty to
contribute to local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half its four million rural surplus laborers go out of
mountains and produce annually 1.6 billion yuan in other provinces
and regions. They buy their families farm machines, improved
seeds, chemical fertilizer, pesticides, and plastic sheets. They
also apply new concepts, skills, and savings to establishing
economic entities back in their hometown. This has greatly
promoted local agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Migrant farmers attribute their good fortune to labor
management offices at all levels. The province initiated the
orderly migration of rural surplus labor forces in 1986, and set
up labor management agencies in Shanghai, Beijing, Xinjiang,
Guangxi, and some other localities.
</P>
<P>
The offices are engaged in employment registration, information
consultation, job recommendation, and market investigation, while
the agencies are busy collecting information and opening up labor
markets. Now the province has established more than 8,000 labor
bases across the country, and joined north China labor force
information network.
</P>
<P>
To ensure an orderly exodus, the province makes it a rule that
migrant farmers get employment registration cards, which help in
finding jobs. In 18 pilot counties, 40 percent of migrant farmers
got the cards last year, and in the capital city of Lanzhou, the
figure exceeded 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The province is making efforts to improve labor force's
quality, by training them in employment centers, agro-science
schools, or vocational schools, to better meet market demands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
