<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Flexes Muscles in Market Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Qi Xinghai, a 56-year-old man of
Xibo ethnic group, handles a number of border trade issues every
day, talking to Kazak, Russian, or inland Chinese businessmen
passing in and out of his office, located near the wire fences
along the border between the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region and
the villages of Kazakstan.
</P>
<P>
Qi, deputy director of the Horgas Port Administrative Committee
of the region, speaks five languages and has become an expert in
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
"We Xibo people once looked down upon businessmen. But now we
do business ourselves, as the reform and opening drive offers us
good opportunities to develop in an all-round way," he says.
</P>
<P>
The Xibos were confined to border areas in the past and could
not live a normal life. But now they enjoy equal rights as other
ethnic groups in China, and are doing well in the market economy.
</P>
<P>
China's western borders have been frequented by traders and
tourists, since military confrontations there with the former
Soviet Union began to relax in the late 1980s. The Xibo people,
accustomed to defending the border areas, embrace the reform
policy with unprecedented open-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
In the 17th century, the Qing Dynasty (1616-1911) reorganized
all the Xibo people into military troops and stationed them along
border areas. Some 4,000 of them made a three-year journey to
Xinjiang and resettled there, charged with opening up wasteland
and guarding the border.
</P>
<P>
The Xibos now have a population of more than 90,000, mainly
distributed over Xinjiang, and northeast China, their
homeland. The group in Xinjiang now numbers over 20,000 people,
mostly living in the Qapqal Xibo Autonomous County. They have
their own spoken and written language, and publish a newspaper
that is said to be the only one of the kind in the world. The
publication, with 1,000 subscriptions, is mainly financed by the
local government
</P>
<P>
Qapqal means granary in the Xibo language. The county has
become a major grain production base since the central government
allowed more freedom for farmland management in the early 1980s.
The Xibo people, expert in farming, are engaged in reclaiming
wasteland, but for quite a different purpose than their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jianxin, 35, a returned student from Japan, is proud of
being a farmer with more than one million yuan worth of fixed
assets. He opened up 200 ha of wasteland two years ago on a loan
of 800,000 yuan. "I like this piece of land and the crops, and I
like to stay at home with my wife and children," he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Aids China in Forest Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-German cooperation
project to improve ecological conditions in northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region is going smoothly.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of last year, Germany donated 12 million marks
for a project to increase forest coverage in the Helan Mountain
area in Ningxia, said Kang Mantang, deputy director of the
forestry department of the regional government. The amount was
half the total investment for the work.
</P>
<P>
Kang said that Ningxia has planted 917 ha of trees, which is 11
percent of the planned workload.
</P>
<P>
The project also includes building fences around mountains that
have well-grown trees and constructing water conservation
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Germany has such aid projects in Beijing, Hebei, Shanxi and
five other provinces in China. 
</P>
