<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Flexes Muscles in Market Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Long-term military services have forged in the Xibos a unique
character. They are patriotic, disciplined, family oriented, and
easy-going in getting along with other ethnic groups. China's
autonomy policy has made it possible for them to preserve and
carry on their fine traditions, while the improved economic
situation is pushing them onto a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
Yong Deguang, a deputy to the National People's Congress, has
submitted 60 proposals over the past four years. "All my proposals
have been dealt with satisfactorily and in particular, our culture
and education are given priority in development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Xibo nationality ranks first for its
biggest percentage of graduate students among China's 56
nationalities. And its living standards are among the best,
according to the UN measurements. The Xibos have an increasing
number of its own scholars with master or doctor degrees, and
those who go and study abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Xibos are really living a happy life today. Bleating of red
deer can be heard occasionally in many cottage courtyards in
Qapqal. Some farmers rely heavily on raising deer. Wu Lingbao is
one of them. The Xibo villager began to breed deer seven years ago
and four years later he set up a deer product processing
factory. Now he becomes a salesman, travelling extensively at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
When asked about their annual income, the hostess Guihua smiled
but said nothing, as a 1.5-metre-high safe and a hand phone beside
in their well-decorated parlour spoke for her. She adopted five
Xibo orphans and a Han child.
</P>
<P>
Her husband says: "success lies mainly in a pioneering spirit
in the market economy. It's out-of-date to live an ordinary life
only by cultivating a small piece of land like our forefathers."
</P>
<P>
Red deer was the Xibo's shooting targets 50 years ago. But now
they show their archery skills at stadia. Qapqal is the cradle of
China's archery, boasting the only county-level shooting gymnasium
in the country. It has trained a number of Xibo athletes, winning
46 national and world championships over the past 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minority Flexes Muscles in Market Economy (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Xibo nationality is experiencing its second leap in
development these years. "The founding of new China in 1949
ensured us extensive political rights, first-ever in our
history. The reform and opening policy has allowed us more room
for economic improvement, and now the emancipated productivity is
boosting a fundamental change in our Xibo people," says Ban Jisu,
deputy director of the Xinjiang Nationalities and Religious
Affairs Commission, and a 60-year-old nationalities expert, who is
of great celebrity among his own people.
</P>
<P>
Ban studied in Beijing in the '50s. He is proud of his
experience. "Beijing was the noble and mysterious capital of the
country in my parents' eyes, only our Xibo military commanders had
ever been there down the ages," he says.
</P>
<P>
He has an amicable family and one of his sons-in-law is a
Han. In Xinjiang, it's not unusual for the Xibo people to marry
people of other ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
The Xibos, known as an "interpreter nationality", are quick at
languages, as they are closely associated with other
nationalities. Primary students are taught in the Xibo language
and standard Chinese, and foreign languages are added in secondary
education. Most of the graduate students know three to four
languages. "This is a breakthrough in China's educational history
and meets the need to train internationally competitive
personnel," says Ban, who is a staunch advocate of the teaching
method.
</P>
<P>
Guli is a 26-year-old Xibo girl. His father married a Uygur
wife. So she knows two languages inherently and picks up Chinese,
Russian and Kazak. Now she finds herself indispensable, working as
an interpreter at the Horgas Port. "I want to go abroad and learn
more languages," she says. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
