<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Layout of Largest Imperial Palace Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Ministers and foreign guests to be
received by emperors of the Tang Dynasty (618-907) had to climb
70-m-long staircases leading up to each end of the Hanyuan Hall on
a ten-m-high platform.
</P>
<P>
The two cases, called Longwei Dao (Road of the Dragon Tail),
turned toward each other to join together right in front of the
hall.
</P>
<P>
This layout was discovered as a result of recent excavations at
the site of Hanyuan Hall. Previously, it was thought that the road
led directly to the hall.
</P>
<P>
Located one km to the north of the present-day Xi'an Railway
Station in this capital of northwest China's Shaanxi Province, the
hall was built in 663, where emperors received officials of the
imperial court and foreign guests, issued imperial verdicts,
granted honors, and reviewed troops.
</P>
<P>
It was ruined with the entire imperial palace complex, Daming
Gong, in the peasant war at the end of the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents have shown that the hall was the largest
imperial palace in China, 300 sq m larger than the major hall in
the prestigious Palace Museum in Beijing where emperors of the
Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties worked.
</P>
<P>
Resting on a ten-m-high platform, the foundation of the Hanyuan
Hall measuring 74.9 m by 41.3 m was found with the remains of
twenty pillar bases in two rows.
</P>
<P>
Two corridors each with a length of 40 m were built at each
side of the hall. The ends of the corridors stretched out to make
the whole structure look like a short "H", with the hall in the
middle of the horizontal line.
</P>
<P>
Remains of watch towers were found at each of the four ends of
the two vertical lines of the "H".
</P>
<P>
Conservation of the hall, backed up by the United Nations
Education, Science, and Culture Organization (UNESCO), has drawn
an aid of one million U.S. Dollars from the Japanese
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
