<HEADLINE> ADB to Increase Assistance to Nepal in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) would like to increase its financial assistance to Nepal in
the future with top priority on agriculture and poverty
alleviation, according to a senior bank official.
</P>
<P>
ADB Vice-President Bong Suk Lee, who is currently here on a
five-day visit to Nepal, said that the bank's programs in Nepal
for 1997 have given priority to the agricultural sector followed
by poverty alleviation in rural areas, official daily the Rising
Nepal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Lee said that ADB assistance to Nepal amounted to almost 80
million US dollars last year with 27 on-going projects and the
bank would like to see the amount of assistance growing over the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
The ADB vice-president met with Nepali Prime Minister Lokendra
Bahadur Chand Sunday to exchange views regarding the bank's
programs in the country with a special focus on poverty
alleviation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
According to Lee, the ADB is seriously considering the issue of
financing a major water supply project in Kathmandu as the Nepali
government is very interested in its implementation.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government planned to implement the 185
million-dollar water diversion project, which will bring water to
Kathmandu from a river 30 km away, to solve the problem of water
shortage in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to supply 170 million liters of water
daily for Kathmandu after the completion of its first phase by
2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
