<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Government Boosts Sustained Growth of Tibet's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAHSA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The central government in China has
allocated more than 20 billion yuan (about 2.4 billion US dollars)
for the sustained and healthy economic development of the Tibet
Autonomous Region since the reform and opening drive was launched
nearly two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
The region's GDP reached 6.5 billion yuan last year, with its
annual economic growth rate maintaining ten percent for two years
running.
</P>
<P>
With huge financial support and preferential policies from the
central government, Tibet has made distinct improvement in its
infrastructure construction, especially in the fields of energy,
communications, and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The construction of large power plants, including the
Yangbajing Geothermal Power Plant, located in the largest
geothermal power test base in China, the Chalong Power Plant, and
a group of county-level power plants, has increased the region's
power generating capacity from 60,000 kilowatts in 1990 to the
current 200,000 kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the two airports in Lhasa, capital of the
autonomous region, the reconstruction of highways linking Tibet to
Xinjiang, Qinghai, Sichuan, and the country of Nepal, and the
laying of fiber optical cables connecting Lhasa with Nyingchi and
Xigaze, have given the region full access to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The Tibet Autonomous Region's economy formerly relied solely on
agriculture and animal breeding, and was marked by a low level of
productivity.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, the central government implemented the household
responsibilty system for both farmers and hurdsmen in the region,
and preferential treatments such as tax reduction and low-interest
loans have been granted to them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Government Boosts Sustained Growth of Tibet's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Provinces and regions across the country have invested 480
million yuan in helping construct 43 projects in Tibet since 1985,
and the improvement in its infrastructure facilities has spurred
the rapid economic growth of the region.
</P>
<P>
The irrigated farm acreage has reached 170,000 ha, with the
total grain output rising to 770,000 tons from over 500,000 tons
in the early 1980s, and good harvests have been recorded for nine
consecutive years. The per capita annual income of farmers has
hit 960 yuan, and 120,000 farmers have been lifted out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises in the fields of electric power,
building materials, textiles, and forestry have improved their
returns, showing new momentum in industrial growth. The total
industrial output rose from 160 million yuan in the early 1980s to
668 million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
A group of new industrial products have put onto the market,
and the region also has had a number of new industrial sectors
such as foreign trade, tourism, township enterprises, and
mining. The total value of import and export hit 116 million US
dollars last year, a six-fold increase over that of 1980, and the
region received 32,000 tourists last year, scoring a business
income of 238 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the country has strengthened its efforts to assist
the region. As many as 3.7 billion yuan were allocated for the
area in 1994, with 62 projects and a large number of technicians
coming in.
</P>
<P>
The region has opened wider to the outside world, drawing more
than 300 million yuan of investment last year, and it is more and
more capable of supporting itself financially. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
