<HEADLINE> Hohhot to Become Economic, Cultural Center in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The capital of Inner Mongolia will
turn into an economic and cultural center in north China by the
year 2010, a local government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot, 669 km away from Beijing, has built several economic
and technological development zones, heavy industrial bases, and
convenient communication networks.
</P>
<P>
The official said the city will boost its economic growth as
the Central Government attaches growing importance to the
development of the central and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Hohhot occupies an area of 17,000 sq. km. with a population of
1.97 million, which include 36 ethnic groups. The city is rich in
water and power resources and has proved reserves of 30 minerals,
laying the foundation for its industrial development.
</P>
<P>
It has formed a relatively complete industrial system with
light and textile industries as the mainstay and an agricultural
system which embraces farming, forestry, animal husbandry and
side-line production, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Its Gross Domestic Product (GDP) has increased at an average
annual rate of 14.3 percent since 1990, climbing to a record 11.3
billion yuan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, The GDP is expecting to reach 27 billion
yuan, double the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The city has unveiled a program to enhance trans-regional
cooperation with neighboring cities. It will join hands with
Baotou to build an industrial corridor along the Beijing-Baotou
railway line, cooperate with Ih Ju League to open up natural
resources and forge economic contacts with coastal areas in China
as well as Russia, Mongolia, and countries in central Asia.
</P>
<P>
As an ancient cultural center, Hohhot has ruins dating back
500,000 years, ancient temples and other historical sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
