<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shabby Villages Turn Into Urban Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Two-decades of economic reform in
China have turned numerous small rural villages into thriving new
urban centers.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, a family clan with several generations lived in
the same village which was named after the family such as Wang's
village or Zhang's village. Head of the family clan had the final
say for everything in the village.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Anhui province, Wang's village, which was still
a dilapidated place in the early 1970s, has now become an urban
center with crisscross traffic, program-controlled telephone
networks, and foreign-funded factories. Its population has swollen
from several hundred to the present 14,000.
</P>
<P>
The village has established trade ties with all parts of China
since it became the largest peanut market in the country.
</P>
<P>
Wang is no longer the dominant clan in the village where
outsiders have come to settle.
</P>
<P>
More than 800 other villages in Anhui have developed into new
urban centers since 1978. Last year, the provincial government
invested 18 billion yuan in the development of satellite towns.
</P>
<P>
Similar experiences were reported in many other provinces in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Huaxi Village in east China's Jiangsu Province yields an
industrial output value of two billion yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
Daqiu village in rural Tianjin, north China, has turned itself
from an impoverished place into an economic rising star in the
country with its gross annual industrial and agricultural output
topping 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Longgang, China's first Peasant Town, is built on a fishing
village in Zhejiang. Its revenue from industrial production in
1996 made up 40 percent of the total industrial output of its
county.
</P>
<P>
Over 300 new towns have emerged in the Pearl River Delta, a
fast-growing area in southern China. The industrial output value
of some towns exceeded three billion yuan a year each.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics have shown that 50,000 new towns have been
built on the foundations of former villages across China since
1978. They have absorbed a great number of surplus rural laborers.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese sociologist attributed the explosion of new towns to
China's rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The national effort to promote the integration of urban-rural
development has accelerated the economic and social development in
rural China which, in turn, has sped up the urban-rural
integration, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
