<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jail Explosion Kills One Prisoner in Columbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- An inmate was killed
in a bomb blast in a high-security jail the capital of Columbia, a
prison spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred late on Saturday in a cell close to the
wing of the La Picota jail where the Cali drug cartel bosses, the
Rodriguez Orejuela brothers, are locked up.
</P>
<P>
The killed man was William Infante, 33, who was handling the
bomb, was a contract killer serving a 24-year term for the murder
of the leader of the left-wing Patriotic Union (UP) party in 1987,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Luis Rodriguez Cuadrado, who was convicted of an assassination
attempt on one of President Ernesto Samper's attorneys, was
seriously injured in the blast.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, "There was an incident in which a prisoner
was handling explosives. We do not yet know exactly what type of
explosive it was." He said it was not yet clear how Infante had
obtained the bomb.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said investigators had ruled out the possibility
that Infante may have died in a bungled escape bid and said there
was no suggestion that the Rodriguez Orejuela brothers, the jail's
star convicts, were in any way involved.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspaper, Infante murdered UP leader Jaime
Pardo Leal on the orders of the late drug trafficker Gonzalo
Rodriguez Gacha, a trusted follower of cocaine kingpin Pablo
Escobar, the late head of the Medellin cartel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
