<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Elections in Nepal to Be Held on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's major political parties
have agreed on holding local elections throughout the country by
June this year, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
An all-party meeting called by the government Sunday
unanimously decided to hold the local elections, which will elect
chief officers for administration bodies on village, municipality
and district levels, on the schedule announced by the former
government last month, according to the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
The present coalition government under Lokendra Bahadur Chand
came to power earlier this month after the former one led by Sher
Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali Congress (NC) party stepped down
following its failure to win a confidence vote in parliament.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a press release of the main opposition NC party said
that the government at the Sunday meeting failed to express its
determination to present a decentralization bill to the on-going
parliament session and hold the local polls after the approval of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
The NC-led government in February decided to postpone the local
elections by two and half months to wait for the introduction of
the decentralization act, which is expected to give more autonomy
to local bodies.
</P>
<P>
The NC party said that it strongly opposed the government's
proposal for concluding the current parliament session soon and
implementing some portion of the decentralization bill through
ordinance.
</P>
<P>
According to Local Development Minister Amrit Bohara, whose
ministry is responsible for conducting the local elections, the
decentralization bill could not be passed before the elections due
to "time constraint and other technical problems".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
