<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 83 Feared Dead in Albanian Shipwreck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 30 (Xinhua) -- At least 83 people were feared dead
when an Albanian refugee boat capsized last Friday off southern
Italy, the Albanian Embassy in Rome confirmed today.
</P>
<P>
In a list faxed to the police authorities of the southern
Italian port Brindisi, the embassy gave the names of 117 people
who were allegedly aboard the ship, which sank on Friday night
after colliding with an Italian naval boat trying to block influx
of illegal Albanian immigrants to Italy.
</P>
<P>
The list, compiled by Ambassador Pandeli Pasko after talking
with survivors, has been handed over to the Interpol for
verification.
</P>
<P>
So far, 34 people have survived the tragedy and four bodies
have been recovered. Survivors said that over half of the
passengers were women and children.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi today promised to
investigate the shipwreck when visiting a refugee camp housing
about 150 Albanians near central Italian city of Bologna.
</P>
<P>
"I have given orders that everything must be clarified in the
fullest and most complete manner," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister avoided the question of whether Italy will
provide political asylum to Albanian refugees, saying the most
urgent thing is to help the Albanian authorities restore order in
the country by sending an Italian-led protection force authorized
by United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"We want to bring assistance to Albania to help it rebuild
itself", he said. "The country must start to live again."
</P>
<P>
More than 13,000 Albanians have flooded into Italy since the
crisis erupted in the Balkan country, triggered by the collapse of
investment schemes that exhausted the savings of thousands of
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Though Italian government has given more than 12,000 Albanians
temporary residence permits this month, it stressed that these
people must be repatriated as soon as the situation in Albanian
returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said today that his country was
not denying anyone's right to asylum, but most of the 13,000
Albanians were not real refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said many of those who have crossed the Adriatic Sea are not
refugees in need of asylum but illegal immigrants hoping to find
jobs in Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
