<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Extracts of White Paper on China's Human Rights Cause in 1996 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of the
State Council released here today a white paper entitled "Progress
in China's Human Rights Cause in 1996," outlining China's
achievements in various domains of its human rights cause in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
The 13,000-character white paper is divided into seven
parts: One: People's Rights to Subsistence and Development;
Two: Citizens' Democratic Rights; Three: Judicial Guarantee for
Human Rights; Four: Protection of Workers' Rights; Five: Citizens'
Rights to Receive Education; Six: Legitimate Rights and Interests
of Women and Children; Seven: Guarantee of Rights of Ethnic
Minorities.
</P>
<P>
The white paper say that the year 1996 was the first year of
implementation of the Ninth Five-Year Plan for the National
economic and Social Development, and also a year that witnessed
continued advances in China's human rights cause.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China's national economy maintained steady, rapid and
sound growth, the efforts to build up democracy and a legal system
were notably strengthened, and the human rights conditions maintained
a good momentum of continuous improvement and promised further
progress.
</P>
<P>
According to the white paper, the people's rights to earn a
living and development recorded a marked improvement. In 1996,
China's national economy continued its rapid growth. The gross
domestic product (GDP) reached over 6,779.5 billion yuan,
representing an increased of 9.7 percent over the previous year,
calculated in terms of comparable prices. The standards of living
for urban and rural people improved nationwide with the steady
increase in people's incomes.
</P>
<P>
The "Engel's coefficient," which indicates the ratio between
the expenses of food and other items of consumption, came to 48.6
percent, or 1.3 percentage points lower than the previous
year. The drop in the "Engel's coefficient" signified a new
improvement of people's living standard.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that while seeking universal improvement
of the people's overall living standard, China has been paying
close attention to meeting people's basic needs for food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
Since the initiation of reform and opening-up, the Chinese
government launched vigorously a nationwide campaign to seek
development and provide assistance for the people in
poverty-stricken areas, which helped reduce the poverty-stricken
population in great numbers for many successive years.
</P>
<P>
The ratio between China's poverty-stricken people and
the world's total has dropped from one-fourth in the 1970s to less
than one-twentieth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China is the country which has witnessed
the quickest decrease in its poverty-stricken population. Since
1978, China's poverty-stricken population has decreased 10 million
every year. China is also working to enable all of its
poverty-stricken people to shake off poverty by the end of this
century.
</P>
<P>
China's development-oriented aid-the-poor work and achievements
in poverty-stricken areas have been universally praised by
international organizations and noted figures.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank believes that "the Chinese government has made
painstaking efforts toward poverty alleviation in the most
backward rural areas. These efforts proved to be much more
successful than those made by many other developing countries."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
