<HEADLINE> Romania to Join Multinational Force in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Romania will send 400-strong
troops to join the Italy-led multinational protection force in
Albania authorized by the United Nations, said a Romanian Defense
Ministry officer here today.
</P>
<P>
Constantin Degeratu, chief of the general staff of the Romanian
Armed Forces, told reporters that the Romanian government
considered it essential to seek humanitarian and political means
to solve the Albania crisis.
</P>
<P>
Romania is ready to provide humanitarian aid to Albania and
join peace-keeping missions in the Balkan country, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the Romanian troops in Albania will protect civilian
and military installations, oversee the delivery of humanitarian
aid materials, set up check points on roads and separate the
conflicting Albanian forces when necessary.
</P>
<P>
It will cost the Romania government 80-100 billion leus (about
11.3-14 million U.S. dollars) to participate in the multinational
protection force in Albania, he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council passed a resolution last Friday,
authorizing the establishment of a temporary and limited
multinational protection force to facilitate the delivery of
humanitarian aid and help restore order in Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
