<HEADLINE> Gold Prices Expected to Rise in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Towards the end of 1997, gold
prices are expected to rise after it was traded between 380 and
415 US dollars per oz from 1994 to 1996 and even fell to a
three-year low of just over 340 dollars in early 1997, according
to a forecast by bankers.
</P>
<P>
The forecast, which appeared in Market Insights monthly today,
said the main causes of the price fall have been weak demand due
to slower growth in Asian incomes, disinvestment out of gold in
response to the strong equities markets, the benign world
inflation outlook, and investors fears of a rise in central bank
sales as European governments reduced debt to meet EMU (European
Monetary Union) entry criteria.
</P>
<P>
However, the bankers said, "towards the end of 1997, the key
date for EMU eligibility, fears of central bank sales will fade.
We also expect to see a rebound in Asian demand and shifts in
investor sentiment back to gold as world growth strengthens and
inflation expectations rise."
</P>
<P>
"While we expect gold to rally to a probable peak of 385
dollars by late 1997, gold prices are more likely to stay below
the old trading range of 380 to 415 dollars and around 370 dollars
per oz over the next several years," they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
