<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yan'an Shakes off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Economically-undeveloped Yan'an in
northwest China's Shaanxi Province has strengthened its campaign
against poverty, having helped 430,000 farmers and nearly 20
townships achieving prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an was the most important base where Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee was headquartered during the War of
Resistance Against Japanese Aggression and the Liberation War.
</P>
<P>
Located in the inner part of the Loess Plateau, the city's
natural conditions are harsh. But Yan'an has concentrated on
developing its agricultural sector, and providing local farmers
with comprehensive services including those for technology,
information and marketing.
</P>
<P>
Preferential policies were also formulated to promote the
development of agriculture, and more than 1,000 cadres went to
over 500 villages to direct the drive against poverty.
</P>
<P>
Local governments at all levels all pay close attention to the
efforts to upgrade farmers' quality of life. More than 300 city
technicians have been working in rural areas, providing farmers
with services such as technological contracting and training in
farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 rural households have learned one or two of
the new skills, and 80 percent of farmers are engaged in business
which brings them stable income.
</P>
<P>
Local governments have also strengthened the building of
infrastructure in the rural areas. By the end of 1996,
the city had completed a 6.5 billion yuan (about 790 million US
dollars) project to provide each village with highways,
electricity, and telephones.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the per capita net income of the city's farmers was
1,120 yuan, and the poverty-stricken population had decreased from
670,000 in 1986 to 240,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thirty Tons of 1,000-year-old Iron Coins Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Two cranes have been used to
unearth 30 tons of iron coins dating back some 1,000 years in the
city of Jiaozhou in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Found at the construction site of a residential building for
city government employees, the coins have rusted into blocks, the
largest of which weighs 14 tons.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts determined, according to identifiable
inscriptions on some of the coins, that they were from the
Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127).
</P>
<P>
They expressed the belief that the site was then a mint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
