<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Historical Sites in Hebei Placed under State Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
added 21 new historical sites to the state protection list early
this year, bringing the total number of local sites to 58.
</P>
<P>
The province and northwest China's Shaanxi Province, frequently
used as capital sites in Chinese history, boast the most historical
sites under state protection.
</P>
<P>
China now has 750 such sites.
</P>
<P>
The newly-added sites in Hebei include a site with human
traces from one million years ago, remains of an imperial resort of
the Qin Dynasty (221-206 BC), and a headquarters of the Eight Route
Army.
</P>
<P>
Rich in religious buildings, Buddhist sculptures, and a long
part of the Great Wall, the province saw many temples and two
passages of the Great Wall added to the recent list.
</P>
<P>
The sites, known to only a few, will be open to the public soon.
</P>
<P>
Previously, sites under state protection in Hebei included an
imperial summer resort in Chengde and imperial tombs from the Qing
Dynasty (1644-1911), city remains of the Zhao State in the Warring
States period (475-221 BC), and a tomb for a king of the Zhongshan
state from which a jade burial suit with gold threads was
unearthed.
</P>
<P>
The sites are now tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
The province has some 720,000 cultural relics, many of which
were unearthed in the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
In the past ten years, for instance, local archaeologists
excavated a total area of 80,000 sq m and more than 1,000 ancient
tombs, unearthing nearly 100,000 cultural relics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henan Protects Large Historical Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A special committee has been
set up in Luoyang City in central China's Henan Province to
protect a capital site of the Han Dynasty (206 BC-220 AD) and the
Wei State during the Three Kingdoms period (220-280).
</P>
<P>
The site is just one of some 200 large historical sites in the
province, which include remains of tribes, cities, pottery, and
porcelain kilns, building groups, imperial mausoleum, and other
tomb groups.
</P>
<P>
Known as the "most complete proof of ancient culture", the
sites, however, usually cover an area of several to tens of
kilometers and are easily damaged by rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem, the province promulgated regulations on
conservation of the sites in 1995, which stipulate that
conservation plans are included in urban planning and allocated
funds accordingly.
</P>
<P>
Local experts are now busy drawing up plans for conserving a
dozen major historical sites, designating the areas within the
sites into places of different importance for more effective
protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More, Better Lawyers in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital now has 3,700
full-time lawyers, three times the number in 1991, according to a
report in today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Hired by 280 law firms, they handled 16,500 criminal, civil,
economic and administrative cases last year, and 7,200 cases
settled out-of-court, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they acted as legal consultants for 4,700
enterprises and recovered 11 billion yuan (1.3 billion US dollars)
in economic losses for their clients, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the country's reform and opening policy and the more
stringent standards for lawyers, many highly qualified people are
attracted to the profession," Jia Wuguang, deputy director of the
Beijing Municipal Justice Bureau, told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
About 50-60 percent of Beijing's lawyers have a bachelor's
degree in law and 13 percent a master's degree or above. Many of
them have worked with law firms in other countries, Jia said.
</P>
<P>
Each year, about 20 Beijing lawyers are sent to other countries
for professional training, he said, adding that a Beijing law firm
even opened a New York branch in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign branches offer good opportunities for Chinese lawyers
to strengthen contacts with foreign lawyers," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 73 law firms of Britain, the United States, France,
Hong Kong, Australia, Japan, Germany, Canada, Italy and Singapore
have been allowed to open offices in China, 34 of which are in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of offices in Beijing by overseas law firms helps
promote the quality and supervision of Beijing lawyers," Jia noted.
</P>
<P>
He also called for self-discipline of the law firms, adding
that local judicial authorities should tighten macro-control over
management of lawyers and law firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Adopts Law to Accept Multinational Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian parliament today
passed a law to welcome deployment of a multinational force to
protect humanitarian relief operations and help restore order in
the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The law, passed with 97 votes for and one against, became
effective immediately from March 30.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the parliament said the law has paved a way for
the relief operations of the European-dominated multinational
force approved by the United Nations last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Friday passed resolution 1101 to
authorize the dispatch of a multinational force led by Italy,
which is expected to consist of 2,500 troops and will enjoy a
three-month mandate for relief operations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Foreign Minister Arjan Starova today said it was
essential that the multinational force be deployed quickly to
oversee relief operations and help stabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
Albania has repeatedly asked for foreign military assistance
since massive protests, sparked by the collapse of pyramid savings
schemes that made thousands of Albanians penniless, turned into
armed revolt earlier this month. More than 150 people were killed
in violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
