<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Ammo from 50 years ago Destroyed in Northeast City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Eleven tons of waste ammunition
left by the Japanese troops some 50 years ago have been destroyed
in Fushun city in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
It took four days to destroy the ammunition -- 1,205 shells,
four air bombs, 154 hand grenades, 20 antitank grenades, and
100,000 detonators -- at the foot of a mountain in Fushun County
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Fushun, some 40 minutes drive from this capital of Liaoning, is
famous for its petrochemical industry and was occupied by Japanese
troops in the War of Resistance to Japanese Aggression
(1937-1945).
</P>
<P>
The ammunition left by the Japanese troops was buried beneath
the bed of a river, and washed away by floods in the summer of
1995. It re-surfaced in the winter after the water iced up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
