<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Wins Brazilian Grand Prix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 30 (AFP) - Jacques Villeneuve survived an off
course trip in his Williams-Renault to take the Brazilian Grand
Prix in Sao Paolo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Veteran Gerhard Berger in a Benetton-Renault was second and
Olivier Panis in the newly-formed Prost team third.
</P>
<P>
It was a dramatic win for the 25-year-old Canadian who, despite
being in pole position, made a mess of the start and went off on
the first bend as he tried to go round the outside of Michael
Schumacher's Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve managed to get his car back onto the circuit after
ploughing across a sand trap but the front nose was damaged and a
trip back to the pits for repairs was certain.
</P>
<P>
But several other drivers had problems at the first bend,
including Ireland's Eddie Irvine in the second Ferrari. Irvine,
invloved in a first bend tussle in the Australian Grand Prix three
weeks ago, clashed with Jan Magnussen's Stewart.
</P>
<P>
With wreckage on the track and Rubens Barrichello in the second
Stewart stuck on the grid, organisers stopped the race and ordered
a restart.
</P>
<P>
A relieved Villeneuve was able to repair his damaged Williams
and get back on to pole spot for the restart, 20 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Despite losing out to Schumacher for a second time in the dash
to the first bend, Villeneuve snatched the lead at the end of the
start-finish straight on the first lap and ran a faultless race.
</P>
<P>
Only Berger, four seconds back, remained in sight of the flying
Villeneuve who went on to collect his fifth grand prix victory in
only his second season.
</P>
<P>
The win put him on top, along with Australian winner David
Coulthard, in the driver's championship. Both men have 10
points. Berger moved into third place, only a point behind, with
Schumacher in fourth, on eight points.
</P>
<P>
Coulthard, who had been struggling all weekend with the
handling of his McLaren Mercedes finished in tenth place, a lap
behind the Canadian.
</P>
<P>
Damon Hill, who failed to even start the opening race of the
season in Australia when his Arrows suffered mechanical trouble,
managed to last 68 of the 72 laps until his engine caught fire as
he drove into the pits.
</P>
<P>
Mika Hakkinen in a McLaren-Mercedes finished fourth ahead of
Michael Schumacher and Jean Alesi in the second Benneton finished
sixth.
</P>
<P>
Heinz-Harald Frentzen, who took Hill's place in the Williams
team, could only finish in ninth spot, well out of the points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muster Beats Bruguera to Win Lipton Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- World number two Thomas Muster
of Austria captured the title of the Lipton tennis championships
by beating Spain's Sergi Bruguera 7-6 (8-6), 6-3, 6-1 in Key
Biscayne, Florida on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Muster, well known as a clay-court specialist, won the
hardcourt tournament over the Spaniard, a surprise conqueror of
world number one Pete Sampras in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
In his 12-year career, Muster had won only one hardcourt title,
in 1990 at Adelaide. Muster has won 43 career ATP titles,
including the 1995 French Open.
</P>
<P>
Bruguera, who had slipped to 81st in the world last year with
injuries, will jump into the ATP top 20 on Monday when the new
ranking was released.
</P>
<P>
The win earned Muster 360,000 U.S. dollars top prize and
Bruguera got 190,000.
</P>
<P>
Muster has a 12-3 lifetime record against Bruguera, the 1993
and 1994 winner of the French Open. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
