<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Review Its  Role in Disbursing Nazi Victims' Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration has
agreed to review whether the U.S. government unfairly confiscated
funds deposited in New York banks by European Jews who may have
perished in the Holocaust, the Washington Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If we are going to shine the spotlight of history on the role
of other countries, then we have an equal obligation to be willing
to shine the spotlight of history on our own involvement," the
Post quoted Commerce Undersecretary Stuart Eizenstat as saying.
</P>
<P>
The issue of U.S. involvement was raised earlier this month in
a letter to Eizenstat from Seymour Rubin, a former State
Department lawyer who served as chief U.S. negotiator during
post-war negotiations with Switzerland over looted Nazi gold
deposited in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
Rubin asserted that at least six million dollars -- equivalent
to 39 million dollars today -- in unclaimed New York bank deposits
may have belonged to Jews murdered by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
The six million dollar estimate may be a small fraction of the
money deposited in the United States by Europeans who later
perished, Rubin said. For one thing, the figure included only sums
deposited in New York, not other U.S. cities. Furthermore, it does
not include all deposits in U.S. branches of Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
The study headed by Eizenstat, now scheduled for release next
month and intended to examine what the U.S. government knew about
the movement of money in Europe before and during the war "will
not complete" without scrutinizing the ultimate fate of such
funds, Rubin said in the letter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970331.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian PM Stresses Good Relations with Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Baschim
Fino, who is expected in Athens on Wednesday at the invitation of
the Greek government, stressed today that the good relations
between the two neighboring countries can not be harmed by
midunderstanding caused by statements of certain Albanian
parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) in
Tirana, which was released here this evening, Fino reiterated the
position of his government regarding the state of Greek-Albanian
relations. He said the parliamentarians can say whatever they
please within the the freedom offered by the institution of
parliament but such statements cannot influence the Greek and
Albanian governments.
</P>
<P>
Some Albanian parliamentarians, including the outgoing Albanian
secret service chief, accused Greece last week of interfering in
the country's internal affairs and plotting to "liberate" southern
Albania.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government rejected such accusations, saying such
claims were "not even worthy of being denied."
</P>
<P>
On his forthcoming visit to Greece, Fino said he believed that
Greece together with Italy have assisted in solving the Albania's
problems, something that the Albanian people are grateful for.
</P>
<P>
"By making contacts and presenting the chaotic situation which
exists in my country, I hope to secure more humanitarian and
financial aid and, at the same time, as the leader of a national
reconciliation government, to stress that we are open and prepared
to co-operate with the Greek government", Fino said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos said
today that Greece would be ready by the end of the week to
contribute an army battalion to the multinational force that will
oversee aid distribution in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Although the minister did not say how many troops Greece would
send to Albania, local press reported that number of such troops
would be around 600-800. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
